{"title_page": "Nadja Malacrida", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{short description|British writer, broadcaster, and socialite}}\n{{Infobox nobility\n| name = Nadja Malacrida\n| title = Marchesa Malacrida de Saint-August\n| image = Nadia Malacrida at marriage, 1922 (cropped).jpg\n| caption = Malacrida at the time of her marriage, 1922\n| birth_name = Louisa Nadia Green\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1895|06|15|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Hampstead]], [[London]], England\n| death_date =  {{death date and age|1934|10|03|1895|06|15|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Henley-on-Thames]], England\n| burial_place = Fairmile Cemetery, [[Henley-on-Thames]]\n| known_for = \n| occupation = {{Flatlist|\n* writer\n* radio broadcaster\n* racing driver\n* socialite\n}}\n| spouse = [[Piero Malacrida de Saint-August]]\n| issue = \n| father = Charles E. Green\n| mother =\n| module = {{Infobox person|embed=yes \n| death_cause = automobile accident}}\n}}\n\n[[File:Ritratto dalla Marchesa Malacrida (1926) by Ettore Tito - Madame de Pompadour version.jpg|thumb|upright|{{lang|it|Ritratto dalla Marchesa Malacrida}} (1926) by [[Ettore Tito]] ]]\n\n'''Louisa, Marchesa Malacrida de Saint-August''' (''n\u00e9e'' '''Louisa Nadia Green''', 15 June 1895 \u2013 3 October 1934), known by the ''[[nom de plume|noms de plume]]'' '''Nadja Malacrida''' and '''Nadja''',  was an English writer, radio broadcaster, racing driver, and socialite. A novelist, playwright, and poet, she published three books of war poetry during the [[First World War]]. An Italian aristocrat by marriage, she was a prominent figure of 20th-century London [[High society (social class)|high society]].\n\n== Early life ==\n\nMalacrida, an only child, was born on 15 June 1895 in [[Hampstead]], London,<ref name=\"1901census\">''1901 England Census''</ref><ref name=\"birth\">''England & Wales, Civil Registration Birth Index, 1837\u20131915''</ref><ref>''Great Britain, Royal Aero Club Aviators' Certificates, 1910\u20131950''</ref> to businessman Charles Edward Green<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=HRA5AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA140&lpg=PA140&dq=charles+e+green+hampstead#v=onepage&q=%22charles+e+green%22&f=false|title=The Jurist |volume=11 |page=140 |date=28 September 1848 |publisher=S. Sweet|via=Google Books}}</ref> and his wife, Louisa Cass.<ref name=\"1901census\"/><ref name=\"1881census\">''1881 England Census''</ref> She grew up at [[Paddockhurst]] in [[West Sussex|Sussex]], the country estate of her uncle and aunt, [[Weetman Pearson, 1st Viscount Cowdray|Weetman Pearson, Lord Cowdray]] (later Viscount) and [[Annie Pearson, Viscountess Cowdray|Annie Cass, Lady Pearson]].<ref name=\"Condon\">{{cite book |last1=Condon |first1=Ian |title=A House Called Paddockhurst: A Short History of Worth's Victorian Mansion |publisher=Worth School |date=February 2010 |page=9 |isbn=978-0956522900 }}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nMalacrida published her first collection of poems, ''Evergreen'', at the age of fourteen.<ref name=\"Evergreen\">[https://archive.org/details/evergreenpoems00nadjiala/page/n7 Preface to the second edition] (1912). Accessed 19 September 2019.</ref> A second edition was published in 1912.<ref name=\"Evergreen\" /> During the War, she published three volumes of poetry: ''Love and War'' (1915), ''For Empire and other poems'' (1916) and ''The full heart'' (1919).<ref name=llbiography>Lucy London (2015). \"Nadja Malacrida (1895\u20131934) poet, writer, & broadcaster\", in the 2015 reprint of ''Love and War''\". Poshupnorth Publishing, [http://www.poshupnorth.com www.poshupnorth.com]. Her year of birth was given as 1895 in this reprint, but later corrected to 1896 by Lucy London.</ref> [[Brian O. Murdoch|Brian Murdoch]] finds Malacrida's war poetry \"well worth rescuing from the obscurity of the lost voices\" and sees some ambiguity in the long poem \"For Empire\" for which the collection ''For Empire and other poems'' is named, with \"very little of the patriotic tonality left\".<ref>[[Brian O. Murdoch|Brian Murdoch]] (1 March 2009). [https://academic.oup.com/english/article/58/220/29/533516 \"For Empire, England's Boys, and the Pageant of War: Women's War Poetry in the Year of the Somme.\"] ''Journal of the English Association'', Volume 58, Issue 220, Spring 2009, Pages 29\u201353. Accessed 21 September 2019.</ref> She donated the proceeds of her war poetry to two First World War charities that still exist as of 2019: St. Dunstan's, a home for soldiers blinded in the war, now with a wider remit under the name [[Blind Veterans UK]], and the Star and Garter Home for Disabled Soldiers, now the [[Royal Star and Garter Home, Richmond]].{{r|llbiography}}\n\nMalacrida and her husband collaborated writing two lightly disguised ''[[Roman \u00e0 clef|romans \u00e0 clef]]'' about the London society scene, using the pseudonym P. N. Piermarini: ''Life Begins To-Day'' (1923) and ''Footprints on the Sand'' (1924).{{r|llbiography}}<ref>[http://explore.bl.uk/primo_library/libweb/action/search.do?fn=search&ct=search&initialSearch=true&mode=Basic&tab=local_tab&indx=1&dum=true&srt=rank&vid=BLVU1&frbg=&tb=t&vl%28freeText0%29=P.+N+Piermarini+&scp.scps=scope%3A%28BLCONTENT%29&vl%282084770704UI0%29=any&vl%282084770704UI0%29=title&vl%282084770704UI0%29=any British Library catalogue]. Accessed 18 September 2019.</ref> She also wrote a play, ''Cheque Mate'', in 1932, using the masculine pen name '''Lewis Hope'''.<ref name=\"Wearing\">{{cite book |last1=Wearing |first1=J. P. |title=The London Stage 1930-1939: A Calendar of Productions, Performers, and Personnel |date=2014 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=9780810893047 |page=211 |edition=2nd}}</ref>\n\nMalacrida took part in an early [[John Logie Baird]] television broadcast in 1933,{{r|llbiography}} and in 1934, the last year of her life, she frequently read mostly Victorian prose excerpts and poetry on [[BBC radio]], under the name '''Nadja Green'''.<ref>[https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/search/20/20?q=Nadja+Green#search ''Radio Times'' 1923\u20132009]. Accessed 19 September 2019.</ref> She also appeared in a national newspaper advertising campaign for [[Vim (cleaning product)|Vim]] household cleaner,{{r|llbiography}} where she was quoted as explaining that it was \"no use having new ideas of decoration if you have old ideas of dirt\"<ref name=\"Vim\" /> and contrasting the dusty hangings and bric-\u00e0-brac of the Victorian era with the simple, spare modern interiors, which must be kept clean because \"every speck and spot is glaringly obvious\".<ref name=\"Vim\" />\n\n== Personal life ==\n\n[[File:Finale - Self-portrait of Nadja Malacrida.jpg|thumb|upright|Cover of ''Finale''. The same image was used as the frontispiece, captioned \"From the painting by [[Ettore Tito]] in the library of [[Dunecht House|Duneckt House]], Aberdeenshire.\"<ref name=Roberts /> That house was also owned by the Cowdrays.<ref>{{Historic Environment Scotland|num=LB3133|desc=Dunecht House|cat=A|mode=cs2|access-date=28 March 2019}}</ref>]]\n\nIn June 1921, Malacrida met her future husband, [[Piero Malacrida de Saint-August|Marchese Piero Malacrida de Saint-August]], an Italian journalist and former cavalry officer, at a charitable fundraising event known as [[Alexandra Rose Day]] at [[The Ritz Hotel, London]].{{r|llbiography}} They were married on 6 December 1922, at [[St Bartholomew-the-Great]],<ref name=\"Sketch-Formerly\">{{cite news |title=Formerly Miss Nadja Green... |work=[[The Sketch]] |date=13 December 1922}}</ref> making her the '''Marchesa Malacrida de Saint-August'''.<ref name=\"de Hegedus\">{{cite news |last1=de Hegedus |first1=Adam |title=A Memorial in Letters |work=The Observer |date=12 January 1936 |page=4}}</ref> Her husband's family were a noble family from [[Lombardy]]. Shortly after their wedding, her husband expanded his activities into writing on interior design, and designing interiors, especially luxury bathrooms, for the upper class. The couple would buy flats at smart London addresses, then remodel and sell them, trading under the name \"Olivotti\".<ref name=\"Vim\">Vim advertisement, ''Nottingham Evening Post'', 16 October 1929, p. 4.</ref><ref name=\"Tinniswood\" /> The Malacridas were celebrities of their time, appearing at all the big society functions, and much reported on in the newspapers of the day.{{r|llbiography}} The marriage was reportedly very happy. They wrote to each other every day when apart,<ref name=Roberts>Cecil Roberts, ed. (1934). ''Finale. Self-portrait of Nadja Malacrida. Correspondence Between Nadja and Piero Malacrida, Aug. 1934.  With a Memoir by Cecil Roberts''.</ref> and their correspondence during her final month was published as ''Finale. Self-portrait of Nadja Malacrida.'' after her death in 1934, including her memoir by the Malacridas' friend [[Cecil Roberts]].<ref name=\"de Hegedus\" /><ref name=Roberts/> \n\nHer portrait in oil was painted in 1926 by [[Ettore Tito]]. It was donated by her husband to the {{lang|it|[[Galleria Internazionale d\u2019Arte Moderna]]}} in 1981,<ref name=\"Ghersetti\">{{cite journal |last1=Ghersetti |first1=Antonella |title=La \"Donazione S.A. Bonebakker\" a Ca' Foscari |url=https://www.unive.it/media/allegato/comunicazione/rivista_cafoscari/2007_aprile.pdf |journal=Cafoscari |date=April 2007 |page=16 |language=it}}</ref> two years before his death. Another portrait, by [[Olive Snell]], featured on the front cover of the 4 December 1929 issue of ''[[The Sketch]]''.<ref name=\"MEPO\">{{cite web |title=Sketch cover - the Marchesa Malacrida |url=https://www.prints-online.com/sketch-cover-marchesa-malacrida-14411509.html |website=Mary Evans Prints Online |accessdate=29 September 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |title=[cover] |magazine=The Sketch |date=4 December 1929 |volume=CXLVIII |issue=1923 |pages=1}}</ref>\n\n== Death ==\n\nOn 3 October 1934, Malacrida was killed in a [[single-vehicle crash]] while driving, alone, back to London from Cecil Roberts' country cottage just outside [[Henley-on-Thames|Henley]].<ref name=\"death\">{{cite news |title=Car's Crash Over Embankment \u2013 Marchesa Malacrida Killed |work=[[The Times]] |publisher=The Times Digital Archive |date=4 October 1934 |page=14 }}</ref> Her car was going uphill when it left the slippery road and plunged down over a 35-foot embankment; she died instantly from a broken neck.<ref name=\"Tinniswood\">{{cite book |last=Tinniswood |first=Adrian |authorlink=Adrian Tinniswood |title=The Long Weekend: Life in the English Country House Between The Wars |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9kcyCwAAQBAJ |publisher=Random House |year=2016 |isbn=978-1-4481-9124-6 |pages=164\u2013169}}</ref> Her body, thrown from the car, was discovered by the groundsman of the Henley Cricket Club while her pet spaniel was discovered later uninjured.<ref name=\"death\"/> She was an experienced and competent driver, who had driven a car for 20 years.{{r|llbiography}} The couple shared a love of fast driving and owned several vehicles including [[Hispano-Suiza]], [[Mercedes-Benz|Mercedes]] and [[Isotta Fraschini]],<ref name=\"Roberts16\">{{cite book |title=Finale. Self-portrait of Nadja Malacrida |first=Cecil |last=Roberts |authorlink=Cecil Roberts |location=London |publisher=Hutchinson & Co |date=1935 |oclc=561516208 |page=16}}</ref> and she had previously driven at [[Brooklands|Brooklands motor racing circuit]].{{r|llbiography}} She is buried at Fairmile Cemetery, [[Henley-on-Thames]].<ref name=\"TMAD\">{{cite news |last1=<!--editor--> |title=Town Marks Armistice Day |url=https://www.henleyherald.com/2014/11/12/town-marks-armistice-day/ |work=Henley Herald |date=12 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The Book of Plans Hopes and Dreams |url=http://www.book-of-phd.com/BoPHD_Screen.pdf |page=106}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Malacrida, Nadja}}\n\n[[Category:1895 births]]\n[[Category:1934 deaths]]\n[[Category:BBC radio presenters]]\n[[Category:Brooklands people]]\n[[Category:English female racing drivers]]\n[[Category:English radio presenters]]\n[[Category:English women dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:English women novelists]]\n[[Category:English women poets]]\n[[Category:English World War I poets]]\n[[Category:English socialites]]\n[[Category:Italian nobility]]\n[[Category:Marchionesses]]\n[[Category:People from Hampstead]]\n[[Category:Road incident deaths in England]]\n[[Category:Women in radio]]\n[[Category:Writers from London]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{short description|British writer, broadcaster, and socialite}}\n{{Infobox nobility\n| name = Nadja Malacrida\n| title = Marchesa Malacrida de Saint-August\n| image = Nadia Malacrida at marriage, 1922 (cropped).jpg\n| caption = Malacrida at the time of her marriage, 1922\n| birth_name = Louisa Nadia Green\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1895|06|15|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Hampstead]], [[London]], England\n| death_date =  {{death date and age|1934|10|03|1895|06|15|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Henley-on-Thames]], England\n| burial_place = Fairmile Cemetery, [[Henley-on-Thames]]\n| known_for = \n| occupation = {{Flatlist|\n* writer\n* radio broadcaster\n* racing driver\n* socialite\n}}\n| spouse = [[Piero Malacrida de Saint-August]]\n| issue = \n| father = Charles E. Green\n| mother =\n| module = {{Infobox person|embed=yes \n| death_cause = automobile accident}}\n}}\n\n[[File:Ritratto dalla Marchesa Malacrida (1926) by Ettore Tito - Madame de Pompadour version.jpg|thumb|upright|{{lang|it|Ritratto dalla Marchesa Malacrida}} (1926) by [[Ettore Tito]] ]]\n\n'''Louisa, Marchesa Malacrida de Saint-August''' (''n\u00e9e'' '''Louisa Nadia Green''', 15 June 1895 \u2013 3 October 1934), known by the ''[[nom de plume|noms de plume]]'' '''Nadja Malacrida''' and '''Nadja''',  was an English writer, radio broadcaster, racing driver, and socialite. A novelist, playwright, and poet, she published three books of war poetry during the [[First World War]]. An Italian aristocrat by marriage, she was a prominent figure of 20th-century London [[High society (social class)|high society]].\n\n== Early life ==\n\nMalacrida, an only child, was born on 15 June 1895 in [[Hampstead]], London,<ref name=\"1901census\">''1901 England Census''</ref><ref name=\"birth\">''England & Wales, Civil Registration Birth Index, 1837\u20131915''</ref><ref>''Great Britain, Royal Aero Club Aviators' Certificates, 1910\u20131950''</ref> to businessman Charles Edward Green<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=HRA5AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA140&lpg=PA140&dq=charles+e+green+hampstead#v=onepage&q=%22charles+e+green%22&f=false|title=The Jurist |volume=11 |page=140 |date=28 September 1848 |publisher=S. Sweet|via=Google Books}}</ref> and his wife, Louisa Cass.<ref name=\"1901census\"/><ref name=\"1881census\">''1881 England Census''</ref> She grew up at [[Paddockhurst]] in [[West Sussex|Sussex]], the country estate of her uncle and aunt, [[Weetman Pearson, 1st Viscount Cowdray|Weetman Pearson, Lord Cowdray]] (later Viscount) and [[Annie Pearson, Viscountess Cowdray|Annie Cass, Lady Pearson]].<ref name=\"Condon\">{{cite book |last1=Condon |first1=Ian |title=A House Called Paddockhurst: A Short History of Worth's Victorian Mansion |publisher=Worth School |date=February 2010 |page=9 |isbn=978-0956522900 }}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nMalacrida published her first collection of poems, ''Evergreen'', at the age of fourteen.<ref name=\"Evergreen\">[https://archive.org/details/evergreenpoems00nadjiala/page/n7 Preface to the second edition] (1912). Accessed 19 September 2019.</ref> A second edition was published in 1912.<ref name=\"Evergreen\" /> During the War, she published three volumes of poetry: ''Love and War'' (1915), ''For Empire and other poems'' (1916) and ''The full heart'' (1919).<ref name=llbiography>Lucy London (2015). \"Nadja Malacrida (1895\u20131934) poet, writer, & broadcaster\", in the 2015 reprint of ''Love and War''\". Poshupnorth Publishing, [http://www.poshupnorth.com www.poshupnorth.com]. Her year of birth was given as 1895 in this reprint, but later corrected to 1896 by Lucy London.</ref> [[Brian O. Murdoch|Brian Murdoch]] finds Malacrida's war poetry \"well worth rescuing from the obscurity of the lost voices\" and sees some ambiguity in the long poem \"For Empire\" for which the collection ''For Empire and other poems'' is named, with \"very little of the patriotic tonality left\".<ref>[[Brian O. Murdoch|Brian Murdoch]] (1 March 2009). [https://academic.oup.com/english/article/58/220/29/533516 \"For Empire, England's Boys, and the Pageant of War: Women's War Poetry in the Year of the Somme.\"] ''Journal of the English Association'', Volume 58, Issue 220, Spring 2009, Pages 29\u201353. Accessed 21 September 2019.</ref> She donated the proceeds of her war poetry to two First World War charities that still exist as of 2019: St. Dunstan's, a home for soldiers blinded in the war, now with a wider remit under the name [[Blind Veterans UK]], and the Star and Garter Home for Disabled Soldiers, now the [[Royal Star and Garter Home, Richmond]].{{r|llbiography}}\n\nMalacrida and her husband collaborated writing two lightly disguised ''[[Roman \u00e0 clef|romans \u00e0 clef]]'' about the London society scene, using the pseudonym P. N. Piermarini: ''Life Begins To-Day'' (1923) and ''Footprints on the Sand'' (1924).{{r|llbiography}}<ref>[http://explore.bl.uk/primo_library/libweb/action/search.do?fn=search&ct=search&initialSearch=true&mode=Basic&tab=local_tab&indx=1&dum=true&srt=rank&vid=BLVU1&frbg=&tb=t&vl%28freeText0%29=P.+N+Piermarini+&scp.scps=scope%3A%28BLCONTENT%29&vl%282084770704UI0%29=any&vl%282084770704UI0%29=title&vl%282084770704UI0%29=any British Library catalogue]. Accessed 18 September 2019.</ref> She also wrote a play, ''Cheque Mate'', in 1932, using the masculine pen name '''Lewis Hope'''.<ref name=\"Wearing\">{{cite book |last1=Wearing |first1=J. P. |title=The London Stage 1930-1939: A Calendar of Productions, Performers, and Personnel |date=2014 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=9780810893047 |page=211 |edition=2nd}}</ref>\n\nMalacrida took part in an early [[John Logie Baird]] television broadcast in 1933,{{r|llbiography}} and in 1934, the last year of her life, she frequently read mostly Victorian prose excerpts and poetry on [[BBC radio]], under the name '''Nadja Green'''.<ref>[https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/search/20/20?q=Nadja+Green#search ''Radio Times'' 1923\u20132009]. Accessed 19 September 2019.</ref> She also appeared in a national newspaper advertising campaign for [[Vim (cleaning product)|Vim]] household cleaner,{{r|llbiography}} where she was quoted as explaining that it was \"no use having new ideas of decoration if you have old ideas of dirt\"<ref name=\"Vim\" /> and contrasting the dusty hangings and bric-\u00e0-brac of the Victorian era with the simple, spare modern interiors, which must be kept clean because \"every speck and spot is glaringly obvious\".<ref name=\"Vim\" />\n\n== Personal life ==\n\n[[File:Finale - Self-portrait of Nadja Malacrida.jpg|thumb|upright|Cover of ''Finale''. The same image was used as the frontispiece, captioned \"From the painting by [[Ettore Tito]] in the library of [[Dunecht House|Duneckt House]], Aberdeenshire.\"<ref name=Roberts /> That house was also owned by the Cowdrays.<ref>{{Historic Environment Scotland|num=LB3133|desc=Dunecht House|cat=A|mode=cs2|access-date=28 March 2019}}</ref>]]\n\nIn June 1921, Malacrida met her future husband, [[Piero Malacrida de Saint-August|Marchese Piero Malacrida de Saint-August]], an Italian journalist and former cavalry officer, at a charitable fundraising event known as [[Alexandra Rose Day]] at [[The Ritz Hotel, London]].{{r|llbiography}} They were married on 6 December 1922, at [[St Bartholomew-the-Great]],<ref name=\"Sketch-Formerly\">{{cite news |title=Formerly Miss Nadja Green... |work=[[The Sketch]] |date=13 December 1922}}</ref> making her the '''Marchesa Malacrida de Saint-August'''.<ref name=\"de Hegedus\">{{cite news |last1=de Hegedus |first1=Adam |title=A Memorial in Letters |work=The Observer |date=12 January 1936 |page=4}}</ref> Her husband's family were a noble family from [[Lombardy]]. Shortly after their wedding, her husband expanded his activities into writing on interior design, and designing interiors, especially luxury bathrooms, for the upper class. The couple would buy flats at smart London addresses, then remodel and sell them, trading under the name \"Olivotti\".<ref name=\"Vim\">Vim advertisement, ''Nottingham Evening Post'', 16 October 1929, p. 4.</ref><ref name=\"Tinniswood\" /> The Malacridas were celebrities of their time, appearing at all the big society functions, and much reported on in the newspapers of the day.{{r|llbiography}} The marriage was reportedly very happy. They wrote to each other every day when apart,<ref name=Roberts>Cecil Roberts, ed. (1934). ''Finale. Self-portrait of Nadja Malacrida. Correspondence Between Nadja and Piero Malacrida, Aug. 1934.  With a Memoir by Cecil Roberts''.</ref> and their correspondence during her final month was published as ''Finale. Self-portrait of Nadja Malacrida.'' after her death in 1934, including her memoir by the Malacridas' friend [[Cecil Roberts]].<ref name=\"de Hegedus\" /><ref name=Roberts/> \n\nHer portrait in oil was painted in 1926 by [[Ettore Tito]]. It was donated by her husband to the {{lang|it|[[Galleria Internazionale d\u2019Arte Moderna]]}} in 1981,<ref name=\"Ghersetti\">{{cite journal |last1=Ghersetti |first1=Antonella |title=La \"Donazione S.A. Bonebakker\" a Ca' Foscari |url=https://www.unive.it/media/allegato/comunicazione/rivista_cafoscari/2007_aprile.pdf |journal=Cafoscari |date=April 2007 |page=16 |language=it}}</ref> two years before his death. Another portrait, by [[Olive Snell]], featured on the front cover of the 4 December 1929 issue of ''[[The Sketch]]''.<ref name=\"MEPO\">{{cite web |title=Sketch cover - the Marchesa Malacrida |url=https://www.prints-online.com/sketch-cover-marchesa-malacrida-14411509.html |website=Mary Evans Prints Online |accessdate=29 September 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |title=[cover] |magazine=The Sketch |date=4 December 1929 |volume=CXLVIII |issue=1923 |pages=1}}</ref>\n\n== Death ==\n\nOn 3 October 1934, Malacrida was killed in a [[single-vehicle crash]] while driving, alone, back to London from Cecil Roberts' country cottage just outside [[Henley-on-Thames|Henley]].<ref name=\"death\">{{cite news |title=Car's Crash Over Embankment \u2013 Marchesa Malacrida Killed |work=[[The Times]] |publisher=The Times Digital Archive |date=4 October 1934 |page=14 }}</ref>\n Her car was going uphill when it left the slippery road and plunged down over a 35-foot embankment; she died instantly from a broken neck.<ref name=\"Tinniswood\">{{cite book |last=Tinniswood |first=Adrian |authorlink=Adrian Tinniswood |title=The Long Weekend: Life in the English Country House Between The Wars |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9kcyCwAAQBAJ |publisher=Random House |year=2016 |isbn=978-1-4481-9124-6 |pages=164\u2013169}}</ref> Her body, thrown from the car, was discovered by the groundsman of the Henley Cricket Club while her pet spaniel was discovered later uninjured.<ref name=\"death\"/> She was an experienced and competent driver, who had driven a car for 20 years.{{r|llbiography}} The couple shared a love of fast driving and owned several vehicles including [[Hispano-Suiza]], [[Mercedes-Benz|Mercedes]] and [[Isotta Fraschini]],<ref name=\"Roberts16\">{{cite book |title=Finale. Self-portrait of Nadja Malacrida |first=Cecil |last=Roberts |authorlink=Cecil Roberts |location=London |publisher=Hutchinson & Co |date=1935 |oclc=561516208 |page=16}}</ref> and she had previously driven at [[Brooklands|Brooklands motor racing circuit]].{{r|llbiography}} She is buried at Fairmile Cemetery, [[Henley-on-Thames]].<ref name=\"TMAD\">{{cite news |last1=<!--editor--> |title=Town Marks Armistice Day |url=https://www.henleyherald.com/2014/11/12/town-marks-armistice-day/ |work=Henley Herald |date=12 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The Book of Plans Hopes and Dreams |url=http://www.book-of-phd.com/BoPHD_Screen.pdf |page=106}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Malacrida, Nadja}}\n\n[[Category:1895 births]]\n[[Category:1934 deaths]]\n[[Category:BBC radio presenters]]\n[[Category:Brooklands people]]\n[[Category:English female racing drivers]]\n[[Category:English radio presenters]]\n[[Category:English women dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:English women novelists]]\n[[Category:English women poets]]\n[[Category:English World War I poets]]\n[[Category:English socialites]]\n[[Category:Italian nobility]]\n[[Category:Marchionesses]]\n[[Category:People from Hampstead]]\n[[Category:Road incident deaths in England]]\n[[Category:Women in radio]]\n[[Category:Writers from London]]\n", "name_user": "Pigsonthewing", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDeath:e", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nadja_Malacrida"}
{"title_page": "Battle of Sari Bair", "text_new": "{{more footnotes|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Battle of Sari Bair\n| partof      = the [[Gallipoli Campaign]] in the [[Middle Eastern theatre of World War I|Middle Eastern Theatre]] of the [[World War I|First World War]]\n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| date        = 6\u201321 August 1915\n| place       = [[Gallipoli]] peninsula, [[Ottoman Empire]]\n| result      = Ottoman victory\n| combatant1  = {{flag|British Empire}}\n* {{flag|Australia}}\n* {{flag|New Zealand}}\n* {{flagcountry|UKGBI}}\n| combatant2  = {{flag|Ottoman Empire}}\n*{{flag|German Empire}} {{small|(Military commanders)}}\n| commander1  = {{flagicon|British Empire}} [[Ian Standish Monteith Hamilton|Ian Hamilton]]\n| commander2  = {{flagicon|German Empire}} [[Otto Liman von Sanders|Liman von Sanders]] <br /> {{flagicon|Ottoman Empire}} [[Faik Pasha]] <br />{{flagicon|Ottoman Empire}} [[Mustafa Kemal Atat\u00fcrk|Mustafa Kemal]]\n| strength1   = 4 divisions (initial)\n| strength2   = Unknown\n| casualties1 = 13,000 dead, wounded, captured or missing\n| casualties2 = 18,000 dead, wounded, captured or missing\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Gallipoli}}\nThe '''Battle of Sari Bair''' ({{lang-tr|Sar\u0131 Bay\u0131r Harek\u00e2t\u0131}}), also known as the '''August Offensive''' ({{lang-tr|A\u011fustos Taarruzlar\u0131}}), represented the final attempt made by the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|British]] in August 1915 to seize control of the [[Gallipoli]] peninsula from the [[Ottoman Empire]] during the [[World War I|First World War]].\n\nAt the time of the battle, the [[Gallipoli Campaign]] had raged on two fronts \u2013 [[Anzac Cove|Anzac]] and [[Landing at Cape Helles|Helles]] \u2013 for three months since the [[Allies (World War I)|Allied]] land invasion of 25 April 1915. With the Anzac front locked in a tense stalemate, the [[Allies (World War I)|Allies]] had attempted to carry the offensive on the Helles battlefield \u2013 at enormous cost and for little gain. In August, the British command proposed a new operation to reinvigorate the campaign by capturing the Sari Bair ridge, the high ground that dominated the middle of the Gallipoli peninsula above the Anzac landing.\n\nThe main operation started on 6 August with a fresh landing {{convert|5|mi|km}} north of Anzac at [[Suvla Bay]] in conjunction with the [[Australian and New Zealand Army Corps (army corps)|Australian and New Zealand Army Corps]]. The Allies mounted an attack north into the rugged country alongside the Sari Bair range with the aim of capturing the high ground and linking with the Suvla landing.  At Helles, the British and [[France|French]] were now to remain largely on the defensive.\n\n== Background ==\nThe battle should properly be known as the \"Battle of ''Koca\u00e7imentepe''\" which was the correct [[Turkish language|Turkish]] name for the ridge and its highest peak (meaning \"Great Grass Hill\").  The peak was known to the British as \"Hill 971\" and they mistakenly applied the name for a lesser ridge to the main range (''Sar\u0131 Bay\u0131r'', meaning \"Yellow Slope\", which ended at the imposing bluff above [[Anzac Cove]] known as \"The Sphinx\").\n\n== Prelude ==\nFor this offensive the commander of the [[Mediterranean Expeditionary Force]], General [[Ian Standish Monteith Hamilton|Sir Ian Hamilton]], was provided with three British [[Kitchener's Army|New Army]] divisions; the [[British 10th (Irish) Division|10th (Irish) Division]], the [[British 11th (Northern) Division|11th (Northern) Division]] and the [[British 13th (Western) Division|13th (Western) Division]] \u2014 all previously untried in [[battle]].  He was later reinforced with two [[Territorial Army (United Kingdom)|Territorial Army]] divisions; the [[British 53rd (Welsh) Division|53rd (Welsh) Division]] and the [[British 54th (East Anglian) Division|54th (East Anglian) Division]] and one division of dismounted [[yeomanry]]; the [[2nd Mounted Division]].{{sfn|Bean|1941|p=440}}\n\nThe Suvla landing was to be made by the [[IX Corps (United Kingdom)|British IX Corps]], under the command of [[Lieutenant-General]] [[Frederick Stopford|Sir Frederick Stopford]]{{sfn|Bean|1941|p=467}} who had retired in 1909 and had never commanded men in battle. His appointment was made based solely on seniority{{sfn|Carlyon|2002|pp=334\u2013335}} but his hesitancy during the preparations for the landing should have warned Hamilton that he was not a fit choice for the command.{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\nThe Ottomans were well aware that a renewal of the offensive was imminent. There had been some doubt about whether the British would abandon the campaign but this was dispelled when [[Winston Churchill]] made a careless speech in [[Dundee]], stating that the battle would continue, whatever the sacrifices. Consequently, the [[Fifth Army (Ottoman Empire)|Fifth Army]] underwent a reorganisation resulting in an expansion to 16 [[division (military)|divisions]]. Ten of these defended the existing battlefields (six at Helles, which had seen the bulk of the early fighting, and four at Anzac). Three divisions defended the Asian shore of the Dardanelles and three divisions of the [[XVI Corps (Ottoman Empire)|Ottoman XVI Corps]] defended the [[Gulf of Saros]] north of [[Bulair]] at the neck of the peninsula.\n\nThe Ottomans anticipated that the offensive would involve a breakout from Anzac but were unsure whether it would be north (towards Suvla) or south (towards [[Gaba Tepe]]). A new British landing was also considered likely but Suvla was not rated highly as a candidate, consequently, only a modest force of four battalions defended the area. The Ottoman commanders also dismissed the possibility of an assault against the Sari Bair range due to the rugged terrain. Only [[Mustafa Kemal Atat\u00fcrk|Mustafa Kemal]], commander of the [[19th Division (Ottoman Empire)|Ottoman 19th Division]] at Anzac, expected the attack against the heights but he was unable to convince his commanding officer, [[Mehmet Esat B\u00fclkat|Esad Pasha]] to significantly strengthen the defenses there. Back in June he had made another attempt, through Captain [[Fahrettin Altay]], then 3. Army chief of staff, to persuade Esad Pasha to beef up defenses further North, but had no result other than raising the ire of his commanding officer.<ref>M. Kemal, \"Anafartalar Muharebatina Ait Tarihce\", Kopernik Kitap (2018), {{ISBN|9752439128}} (collection of communications related to Anafarta battles)</ref> To placate him, only one [[regiment]], 14. was moved to the sector north of Anzac.{{sfn|Cameron|2009|pp=19\u201320}}\n\n==Battle==\n===Anzac breakout ===\n[[File:Battle of Sari Bair, first phase.jpg|thumb|<center>Map of the British attack, 6\u20138 August</center>]]\nThe attack from the Anzac perimeter was directed against two peaks of the Sari Bair range; [[Chunuk Bair]] and Hill 971.{{sfn|Bean|1941|pp=455\u2013456}} Under the overall command of [[Major-General]] [[Alexander Godley]], the attacking force included the [[New Zealand and Australian Division]], the British [[British 13th (Western) Division|13th Division]] plus a couple of extra infantry [[brigade]]s.{{sfn|Bean|1941|p=454}}\n\nThe plan was for two assaulting columns to march out of Anzac on the night of 6 August. The right-hand column, comprising the [[New Zealand Infantry Brigade]] under [[Brigadier-General]] Francis Johnston, would head for Chunuk Bair.{{sfn|Bean|1941|p=459}}  The left-hand column, commanded by Major-General [[Herbert Cox]], heading for Hill 971 and neighbouring Hill Q, contained the [[4th Brigade (Australia)|Australian 4th Infantry Brigade]] of Brigadier-General [[John Monash]] and Cox's [[29th Indian Brigade]].{{sfn|Bean|1941|pp=460\u2013461}} Both objectives were expected to be captured by dawn.{{sfn|Bean|1941|p=463}}\n\nTo distract the Ottomans from the impending offensive, on 6 August, at 5.30 p.m., an attack was made at [[Battle of Lone Pine|Lone Pine]] by the infantry brigades of the [[Australian 1st Division (World War I)|Australian 1st Division]]. While the attack was ultimately successful in capturing the Ottoman trenches, it was counterproductive as a diversion as it attracted reinforcements to the north.  Another costly diversion was carried out at Helles which resulted in a pointless struggle over a patch of ground known as [[Battle of Krithia Vineyard|Krithia Vineyard]].  As was the case at Lone Pine, the British action at Helles did not restrain the Ottomans from sending reinforcements north to the Sari Bair range.\n\nThe right column heading for Chunuk Bair had a simpler navigation task as their route was to some degree visible from the old Anzac perimeter. In what became known as the [[Battle of Chunuk Bair]], the [[Dominion of New Zealand|New Zealanders]] failed to capture the peak by the morning of 7 August but managed the feat on the next morning.\n\n[[File:Battle of Sari Bair, second phase.jpg|thumb|<center>Map of the Turkish counter-attack, 9\u201310 August</center>]]\nOn the morning following the breakout, a number of other attacks were planned within the old Anzac perimeter. The most notorious was the attack of the [[Australian 3rd Light Horse Brigade]] at [[Battle of the Nek|The Nek]] whose slim chance of success had depended on the New Zealanders having captured Chunuk Bair on schedule.\n\nThe left column's journey through the tangled ravines was doomed to failure and, having become lost and confused, it never got close to the objective of Hill 971.  By the morning of 8 August Cox's forces were sufficiently organised to attempt an attack on their original objectives of Hill 971 and Hill Q. However Monash's brigade was still mistaken about its position relative to Hill 971. In fact, by the end of the day's advance Monash's troops had actually reached the position they had believed they had been starting from. Meanwhile, Hill 971 was more unreachable than ever. The three Australian [[battalion]]s that had made the assault suffered 765 casualties \u2014 the [[15th Battalion (Australia)|15th Battalion]] was reduced to about 30 per cent of its normal strength.\n\nOf the force aiming for Hill Q, one battalion of the [[6th Queen Elizabeth's Own Gurkha Rifles|6th Gurkhas]] commanded by [[Major]] [[Cecil Allanson]] and joined by disparate New Army men, moved to within 200 feet of Hill Q by 6 p.m. on 8 August where they sought shelter from the heavy Ottoman fire.  After a [[naval artillery]] bombardment, the battalion attacked the summit shortly after 5 a.m. on 9 August. The plan of the attack, as concocted by General Godley, had involved numerous other battalions but all were lost or pinned down so the Gurkhas went on alone. They succeeded in driving the Ottomans off the hill but were then caught in further naval gunfire from friendly [[monitor warship type|monitors]] or from an [[artillery battery]] at Anzac. Having suffered heavy casualties and with no reinforcements, Allanson's force was pushed back off the hill shortly afterwards.\n\nBy the end of 9 August the Allies retained only a foothold on Chunuk Bair. On 10 August the Ottomans, led from the front by Colonel Mustafa Kemal, counter-attacked and regained control of the entire Sari Bair ridge.\n\n''See also:'' [[Battle of Krithia Vineyard]] \u2014 [[Battle of Lone Pine]] \u2014 [[Battle of the Nek]] \u2014 [[Battle of Chunuk Bair]]\n\n=== Suvla landing ===\n{{main|Landing at Suvla Bay}}\nStopford's IX Corps comprised the British [[10th Division (British)|10th (Irish)]] and [[11th Division (British)|11th Divisions]]. At the time of the landing on 6 August the British were confronted by three Ottoman battalions under the command of a [[Bavaria]]n [[cavalry]] officer, [[Major]] [[Wilhelm Willmer]] whose task was to delay the British until reinforcements could arrive from Bulair, {{convert|30|mi|km}} away.\n\nStopford, who had decided to command the landings from [[Acacia-class sloop|HMS ''Jonquil'']] that was anchored offshore, slept during the attack instead.<ref>[http://www.firstworldwar.com/bio/stopford.htm Biography at firstworldwar.com]</ref> The 11th Division landed on the night of 6 August and two brigades of the 10th Division landed the following morning. The landings, made in the dark without the aid of reliable [[reconnaissance]], suffered from the same confusion that reigned at [[landing at Anzac Cove|Anzac landing]] on 25 April. Lighters ran aground on sandbars so that the troops had to wade some distance to get ashore. Many units became intermingled and officers were unable to locate their objectives. [[Lala Baba]] was captured by the 6th Battalion of the [[Green Howards|Yorkshire Regiment]] in what was the first combat action by any unit of the [[Kitchener's Army|New Army]] of [[Horatio Kitchener, 1st Earl Kitchener of Khartoum|Lord Kitchener]]. The original objectives were the capture of the ridge lines to the north (Kiretch Tepe) and east (Tekke Tepe) and the line of hills to the south on the Anafarta Spur. Stopford's 'caution' and Hamilton's failure to exert his will on his subordinate commanders, meant the objectives were diluted to little more than securing the beach.\n\nBy evening on 7 August, with the [[chain of command]] breaking down, progress had become minimal. Mostly due to Stopford still \"commanding\" from offshore, however, a lack of supplies, especially drinking water, weren't helping matters. To the south east Chocolate Hill and Green Hill were taken in the evening with minimal resistance but constant harassment by [[Shrapnel shell|shrapnel]] and [[sniper]] fire. The British suffered {{nowrap|1,700 casualties}} on the first day at Suvla.\n\nGeneral Sanders was incensed at commander of the 7th and 12th divisions, Colonel Fevzi Bey, for not taking advantage of the Allied disarray at Suvla and pounce on them before they got organized. Turks not expecting a major landing at Suvla had to rush in the two divisions and Fevzi Bey dreaded night attacks, which were rarely successful.<ref>\"Dirilis\", Turgut Ozakman, Bilgi Yayinevi, 2018, pp. 440\u2013470</ref> Sanders relieved Fevzi Bey immediately and gave the responsibility to [[Mustafa Kemal]] who was the commander of the 19th division. Basically he was given the command of a whole group responsible for the front from Anzac Cove to [[Gulf of Saros|Saros]]. He immediately planned for an attack along the Anafarta Hills. Given his success at Ariburnu earlier in spring, Mustafa Kemal's arrival boosted the Ottoman morale.\n\nThe first serious Allied attempt at the ridges of the Anafarta Hills to the east was made on the night of 8 August, following intervention from Hamilton but on the morning of 9 August, the Ottoman reinforcements had begun to arrive and the British were driven back. The fighting concentrated around [[Scimitar Hill]] which protruded northwards from the Anafarta Spur and dominated the southern approach to the Tekke Tepe ridge. Scimitar Hill had been captured then abandoned on 8 August; attempts to retake the hill on 9 and 10 August, were thwarted by the Ottomans. The gunfire was so intense it set the undergrowth ablaze and many of the wounded were incinerated where they lay.\n\nAs the fighting developed, the landing was reinforced by the arrival of the British [[53rd Division (British)|53rd Division]] on 9 August, followed by the [[54th Division (British)|54th Division]] on 10 August.  Stopford now had four divisions under his corps command but was faced by a similar strength of Ottoman defenders. The 53rd Division was mauled in another attack on Scimitar Hill on 10 August.\n\nOn 15 August, Hamilton sacked Stopford and a number of division and brigade commanders. The command of IX Corps was given to Major-General [[Beauvoir De Lisle]], commander of the [[British 29th Division|29th Division]] until Lieutenant-General [[Julian H.G. Byng, 1st Viscount Byng of Vimy|Julian Byng]] could travel from France to assume command.\n\n== Aftermath ==\n\n===Analysis===\n[[File:Southern Trench in Lone Pine, Gallipoli, 8 August 1915 (Graphic Content) (17797424431).jpg|alt=Southern Trench in Lone Pine, Gallipoli, 8 August 1915|thumb|Southern Trench in Lone Pine, Gallipoli, 8 August 1915]]\nOnce the battles of 21 August had finished, the front lines at Suvla and Anzac remained static for the remainder of the campaign. Localised fighting continued but no more major advances were attempted. Many soldiers suffered or perished due to the hostile conditions they endured as a result of their poor preparation and training. Disease transmitted by mosquitoes and the lack of fresh water and shelter hampered the efforts of the division as the men were too weak to fight to their best ability. The insufficient knowledge had an impact of their advancement as their enemy were more familiar to the terrain and could ambush the division successfully. A combination of factors caused their success to be mixed.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Tenth (Irish) Division in Gallipoli|last=1884\u20131930.|first=Cooper, Bryan|date=1993|publisher=Irish Academic Press|isbn=0716525178|location=Dublin, Ireland|oclc=29797013}}</ref>\n\n===Subsequent operations===\n{{main|Battle of Scimitar Hill|Battle of Hill 60 (Gallipoli)}}\n\nAs the shape of the new front line firmed, General Hamilton planned one further attack to try to link the Suvla landing to Anzac. This required the capture of a group of hills; Scimitar Hill and the 'W' Hills from Suvla and Hill 60 from the new Anzac sector. The attacks were to commence on 21 August. At Suvla, de Lisle had his 29th Division and the [[2nd Mounted Division]] which had been moved to Suvla as additional reinforcements.\n\nThe 29th Division was to attack [[Battle of Scimitar Hill|Scimitar Hill]] while the 11th Division was to take the W Hills on the south of the Anafarta Spur. The 2nd Mounted Division was in reserve near Lala Baba on the far side of the salt lake. This attack was the largest mounted by the Allies at Gallipoli. Scimitar Hill was captured briefly but the attackers were driven off or killed by the defensive fire from the Ottomans higher up the spur. Once again the undergrowth ignited, burning many of the wounded. The 2nd Mounted Division were called to join the attack and advanced, marching in extended formation, straight across the salt lake, under fire the whole way. For a second time the hill was captured, briefly, before being lost for the final time.  The attack of the 11th Division towards the W Hills was held up by strong Ottoman defences.\n\nIn the Anzac sector, Hill 60 had been unoccupied on the morning of 7 August, when [[Military history of Australia during World War I|Australian]] scouts passed across but the Ottomans swiftly occupied and fortified the hill. The [[Battle of Hill 60 (Gallipoli)|Battle of Hill 60]] lasted for eight days and while the summit was eventually reached, the Allies were unable to completely dislodge the sacrificially fighting Ottoman defenders.\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |ref=\n|series=History of the Great War Based on Official Documents by Direction of the Historical Section of the Committee of Imperial Defence |title=Military Operations Gallipoli: Inception of the Campaign to May 1915 |volume=I |last=Aspinall-Oglander |first=C. F. | authorlink= |year=1929 |publisher=Heinemann|location=London| edition= |oclc=464479053}}\n* {{cite book |ref=\n|series=History of the Great War Based on Official Documents by Direction of the Historical Section of the Committee of Imperial Defence |title=Military Operations Gallipoli: May 1915 to the Evacuation |volume=II |last=Aspinall-Oglander |first=C. F. |authorlink= |year=1932 |publisher=Heinemann|location=London| edition=IWM & Battery Press 1992 |isbn=0-89839-175-X}}\n* {{cite book |ref=\n|url=https://www.awm.gov.au/collection/RCDIG1069750/|title=The Story of ANZAC from the Outbreak of War to the End of the First Phase of the Gallipoli Campaign, May 4, 1915 | year=1921 |first=C. E. W. |last=Bean |location=Sydney |publisher=Angus and Robertson |series=[[Official History of Australia in the War of 1914\u20131918]] |edition=11th, 1941 |volume=I |oclc=220878987}}\n* {{cite book |ref=harv\n|url=https://www.awm.gov.au/collection/RCDIG1069751/|title=The Story of Anzac from 4 May 1915, to the Evacuation of the Gallipoli Peninsula |volume=II |series=Official History of Australia in the War of 1914\u20131918 |year=1941 |origyear=1921 |first=C. E. W. |last=Bean |authorlink=Charles Bean |edition=11th |location=Canberra |publisher=Australian War Memorial |oclc=39157087}}\n* {{Cite book |ref={{harvid|Cameron|2009}}|title='Sorry, lads, but the order is to go' : the August Offensive, Gallipoli : 1915 |last=Cameron |first=David W. |date=2009 |publisher=UNSW Press |isbn=9781742230788 |location=Sydney, Australia |oclc=647917261}}\n*{{cite book|last=Carlyon|first=Les|title=Gallipoli|year=2002|publisher=Picador Australia|location=|isbn=0732911281|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |ref=\n|title=The Tenth (Irish) Division in Gallipoli |last=Cooper |first=B. |year=1918 |publisher=Herbert Jenkins |location=London |edition=1st |url=https://archive.org/details/tenthirishdivisi00cooprich |accessdate=7 August 2014 |oclc=253010093}}\n* {{cite book |ref=\n|title=The Story of the 29th Division, A Record of Gallant Deeds |last=Gillon |first=S. |authorlink= |year=1925 |publisher=Thomas Nelson |location=London |edition=N & M Press 2002 |isbn=1-84342-265-4}}\n* {{cite book |ref=\n|title=Gallipoli Diary |volume=I |last=Hamilton |first=I. S. M. |year=1920 |publisher=Edward Arnold |location=London |edition= |url=https://archive.org/details/cu31924088057215 |accessdate=7 August 2014 |oclc=816494856}}\n* {{cite book |ref=\n|title=Gallipoli Diary |volume=II |last=Hamilton |first=I. S. M. |year=1920 |publisher=Edward Arnold |location=London |edition= |url=https://archive.org/details/cu31924088057223 |accessdate=7 August 2014 |oclc=816494856}}\n* {{cite book |ref=\n|last=Sanders |first=O. V. K. Liman von |authorlink=Otto Liman von Sanders |title=F\u00fcnf Jahre T\u00fcrkei |trans-title=Five Years in Turkey |year=1919 |language=German |publisher=Scherl |location=Berlin |edition=1st |url=https://archive.org/details/fnfjahretrke00limauoft |accessdate=7 August 2014 |oclc=69108964}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{portal|World War I}}\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{Cite book|last= Chambers|first=Stephen\n|title=Anzac: Sari Bair |publisher = Pen & Sword Military|date=2014|isbn =9781781591901 |oclc=882892566}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Haythornthwaite|first=Philip J. \n|title=Gallipoli, 1915: Frontal Assault on Turkey |publisher =Osprey |date=1991|isbn = 1855321114|oclc=28115553}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Prior |first=Robin |title=Gallipoli: The End of the Myth |publisher=Yale University Press |date=2009 |isbn=9780300149951 |oclc=263409075 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/gallipoliendofmy00robi }}\n*{{Cite book|last=Stanley |first=Peter\n|title=Die in battle, do not despair: the Indians on Gallipoli, 1915 |publisher =Helion & Company Limited |date=2015|isbn =9781910294673 |oclc=898163549}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{coord missing|Turkey}}\n\n{{World War I}}\n{{Ottoman battles in the 20th century}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sari Bair}}\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1915]]\n[[Category:Battles of World War I involving Australia]]\n[[Category:Battles of the Gallipoli Campaign]]\n[[Category:Battles of World War I involving British India]]\n[[Category:Battles of World War I involving New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Battles of World War I involving the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:Battles of World War I involving the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Mustafa Kemal Atat\u00fcrk]]\n[[Category:History of \u00c7anakkale]]\n[[Category:1915 in the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:August 1915 events]]\n", "text_old": "{{more footnotes|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Battle of Sari Bair\n| partof      = the [[Gallipoli Campaign]] in the [[Middle Eastern theatre of World War I|Middle Eastern Theatre]] of the [[World War I|First World War]]\n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| date        = 6\u201321 August 1915\n| place       = [[Gallipoli]] peninsula, [[Ottoman Empire]]\n| result      = Ottoman victory\n| combatant1  = {{flag|British Empire}}\n* {{flag|Australia}}\n* {{flag|New Zealand}}\n* {{flagcountry|UKGBI}}\n| combatant2  = {{flag|Ottoman Empire}}\n*{{flag|German Empire}} {{small|(Military commanders)}}\n| commander1  = {{flagicon|British Empire}} [[Ian Standish Monteith Hamilton|Ian Hamilton]]\n| commander2  = {{flagicon|German Empire}} [[Otto Liman von Sanders|Liman von Sanders]] <br /> {{flagicon|Ottoman Empire}} [[Faik Pasha]] <br />{{flagicon|Ottoman Empire}} [[Mustafa Kemal Atat\u00fcrk|Mustafa Kemal]]\n| strength1   = 4 divisions (initial)\n| strength2   = Unknown\n| casualties1 = 13,000 dead, wounded, captured or missing\n| casualties2 = 18,000 dead, wounded, captured or missing\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Gallipoli}}\nThe '''Battle of Sari Bair''' ({{lang-tr|Sar\u0131 Bay\u0131r Harek\u00e2t\u0131}}), also known as the '''August Offensive''' ({{lang-tr|A\u011fustos Taarruzlar\u0131}}), represented the final attempt made by the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|British]] in August 1915 to seize control of the [[Gallipoli]] peninsula from the [[Ottoman Empire]] during the [[World War I|First World War]].\n\nAt the time of the battle, the [[Gallipoli Campaign]] had raged on two fronts \u2013 [[Anzac Cove|Anzac]] and [[Landing at Cape Helles|Helles]] \u2013 for three months since the [[Allies (World War I)|Allied]] land invasion of 25 April 1915. With the Anzac front locked in a tense stalemate, the [[Allies (World War I)|Allies]] had attempted to carry the offensive on the Helles battlefield \u2013 at enormous cost and for little gain. In August, the British command proposed a new operation to reinvigorate the campaign by capturing the Sari Bair ridge, the high ground that dominated the middle of the Gallipoli peninsula above the Anzac landing.\n\nThe main operation started on 6 August with a fresh landing {{convert|5|mi|km}} north of Anzac at [[Suvla Bay]] in conjunction with the [[Australian and New Zealand Army Corps (army corps)|Australian and New Zealand Army Corps]]. The Allies mounted an attack north into the rugged country alongside the Sari Bair range with the aim of capturing the high ground and linking with the Suvla landing.  At Helles, the British and [[France|French]] were now to remain largely on the defensive.\n\n== Background ==\nThe battle should properly be known as the \"Battle of ''Koca\u00e7imentepe''\" which was the correct [[Turkish language|Turkish]] name for the ridge and its highest peak (meaning \"Great Grass Hill\").  The peak was known to the British as \"Hill 971\" and they mistakenly applied the name for a lesser ridge to the main range (''Sar\u0131 Bay\u0131r'', meaning \"Yellow Slope\", which ended at the imposing bluff above [[Anzac Cove]] known as \"The Sphinx\").\n\n== Prelude ==\nFor this offensive the commander of the [[Mediterranean Expeditionary Force]], General [[Ian Standish Monteith Hamilton|Sir Ian Hamilton]], was provided with three British [[Kitchener's Army|New Army]] divisions; the [[British 10th (Irish) Division|10th (Irish) Division]], the [[British 11th (Northern) Division|11th (Northern) Division]] and the [[British 13th (Western) Division|13th (Western) Division]] \u2014 all previously untried in [[battle]].  He was later reinforced with two [[Territorial Army (United Kingdom)|Territorial Army]] divisions; the [[British 53rd (Welsh) Division|53rd (Welsh) Division]] and the [[British 54th (East Anglian) Division|54th (East Anglian) Division]] and one division of dismounted [[yeomanry]]; the [[2nd Mounted Division]].{{sfn|Bean|1941|p=440}}\n\nThe Suvla landing was to be made by the [[IX Corps (United Kingdom)|British IX Corps]], under the command of [[Lieutenant-General]] [[Frederick Stopford|Sir Frederick Stopford]]{{sfn|Bean|1941|p=467}} who had retired in 1909 and had never commanded men in battle. His appointment was made based solely on seniority{{sfn|Carlyon|2002|pp=334\u2013335}} but his hesitancy during the preparations for the landing should have warned Hamilton that he was not a fit choice for the command.{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\nThe Ottomans were well aware that a renewal of the offensive was imminent. There had been some doubt about whether the British would abandon the campaign but this was dispelled when [[Winston Churchill]] made a careless speech in [[Dundee]], stating that the battle would continue, whatever the sacrifices. Consequently, the [[Fifth Army (Ottoman Empire)|Fifth Army]] underwent a reorganisation resulting in an expansion to 16 [[division (military)|divisions]]. Ten of these defended the existing battlefields (six at Helles, which had seen the bulk of the early fighting, and four at Anzac). Three divisions defended the Asian shore of the Dardanelles and three divisions of the [[XVI Corps (Ottoman Empire)|Ottoman XVI Corps]] defended the [[Gulf of Saros]] north of [[Bulair]] at the neck of the peninsula.\n\nThe Ottomans anticipated that the offensive would involve a breakout from Anzac but were unsure whether it would be north (towards Suvla) or south (towards [[Gaba Tepe]]). A new British landing was also considered likely but Suvla was not rated highly as a candidate, consequently, only a modest force of four battalions defended the area. The Ottoman commanders also dismissed the possibility of an assault against the Sari Bair range due to the rugged terrain. Only [[Mustafa Kemal Atat\u00fcrk|Mustafa Kemal]], commander of the [[19th Division (Ottoman Empire)|Ottoman 19th Division]] at Anzac, expected the attack against the heights but he was unable to convince his commanding officer, [[Mehmet Esat B\u00fclkat|Esad Pasha]] to significantly strengthen the defenses there. Back in June he had made another attempt, through Captain [[Fahrettin Altay]], then 3. Army chief of staff, to persuade Esad Pasha to beef up defenses further North, but had no result other than raising the ire of his commanding officer.<ref>M. Kemal, \"Anafartalar Muharebatina Ait Tarihce\", Kopernik Kitap (2018), {{ISBN|9752439128}} (collection of communications related to Anafarta battles)</ref> To placate him, only one [[regiment]], 14. was moved to the sector north of Anzac.{{sfn|Cameron|2009|pp=19\u201320}}\n\n==Battle==\n===Anzac breakout ===\n[[File:Battle of Sari Bair, first phase.jpg|thumb|<center>Map of the British attack, 6\u20138 August</center>]]\nThe attack from the Anzac perimeter was directed against two peaks of the Sari Bair range; [[Chunuk Bair]] and Hill 971.{{sfn|Bean|1941|pp=455\u2013456}} Under the overall command of [[Major-General]] [[Alexander Godley]], the attacking force included the [[New Zealand and Australian Division]], the British [[British 13th (Western) Division|13th Division]] plus a couple of extra infantry [[brigade]]s.{{sfn|Bean|1941|p=454}}\n\nThe plan was for two assaulting columns to march out of Anzac on the night of 6 August. The right-hand column, comprising the [[New Zealand Infantry Brigade]] under [[Brigadier-General]] Francis Johnston, would head for Chunuk Bair.{{sfn|Bean|1941|p=459}}  The left-hand column, commanded by Major-General [[Herbert Cox]], heading for Hill 971 and neighbouring Hill Q, contained the [[4th Brigade (Australia)|Australian 4th Infantry Brigade]] of Brigadier-General [[John Monash]] and Cox's [[29th Indian Brigade]].{{sfn|Bean|1941|pp=460\u2013461}} Both objectives were expected to be captured by dawn.{{sfn|Bean|1941|p=463}}\n\nTo distract the Ottomans from the impending offensive, on 6 August, at 5.30 p.m., an attack was made at [[Battle of Lone Pine|Lone Pine]] by the infantry brigades of the [[Australian 1st Division (World War I)|Australian 1st Division]]. While the attack was ultimately successful in capturing the Ottoman trenches, it was counterproductive as a diversion as it attracted reinforcements to the north.  Another costly diversion was carried out at Helles which resulted in a pointless struggle over a patch of ground known as [[Battle of Krithia Vineyard|Krithia Vineyard]].  As was the case at Lone Pine, the British action at Helles did not restrain the Ottomans from sending reinforcements north to the Sari Bair range.\n\nThe right column heading for Chunuk Bair had a simpler navigation task as their route was to some degree visible from the old Anzac perimeter. In what became known as the [[Battle of Chunuk Bair]], the [[Dominion of New Zealand|New Zealanders]] failed to capture the peak by the morning of 7 August but managed the feat on the next morning.\n\n[[File:Battle of Sari Bair, second phase.jpg|thumb|<center>Map of the Turkish counter-attack, 9\u201310 August</center>]]\nOn the morning following the breakout, a number of other attacks were planned within the old Anzac perimeter. The most notorious was the attack of the [[Australian 3rd Light Horse Brigade]] at [[Battle of the Nek|The Nek]] whose slim chance of success had depended on the New Zealanders having captured Chunuk Bair on schedule.\n\nThe left column's journey through the tangled ravines was doomed to failure and, having become lost and confused, it never got close to the objective of Hill 971.  By the morning of 8 August Cox's forces were sufficiently organised to attempt an attack on their original objectives of Hill 971 and Hill Q. However Monash's brigade was still mistaken about its position relative to Hill 971. In fact, by the end of the day's advance Monash's troops had actually reached the position they had believed they had been starting from. Meanwhile, Hill 971 was more unreachable than ever. The three Australian [[battalion]]s that had made the assault suffered 765 casualties \u2014 the [[15th Battalion (Australia)|15th Battalion]] was reduced to about 30 per cent of its normal strength.\n\nOf the force aiming for Hill Q, one battalion of the [[6th Queen Elizabeth's Own Gurkha Rifles|6th Gurkhas]] commanded by [[Major]] [[Cecil Allanson]] and joined by disparate New Army men, moved to within 200 feet of Hill Q by 6 p.m. on 8 August where they sought shelter from the heavy Ottoman fire.  After a [[naval artillery]] bombardment, the battalion attacked the summit shortly after 5 a.m. on 9 August. The plan of the attack, as concocted by General Godley, had involved numerous other battalions but all were lost or pinned down so the Gurkhas went on alone. They succeeded in driving the Ottomans off the hill but were then caught in further naval gunfire from friendly [[monitor warship type|monitors]] or from an [[artillery battery]] at Anzac. Having suffered heavy casualties and with no reinforcements, Allanson's force was pushed back off the hill shortly afterwards.\n\nBy the end of 9 August the Allies retained only a foothold on Chunuk Bair. On 10 August the Ottomans, led from the front by Colonel Mustafa Kemal, counter-attacked and regained control of the entire Sari Bair ridge.\n\n''See Also:'' [[Battle of Krithia Vineyard]] \u2014 [[Battle of Lone Pine]] \u2014 [[Battle of the Nek]] \u2014 [[Battle of Chunuk Bair]]\n\n=== Suvla landing ===\n{{main|Landing at Suvla Bay}}\nStopford's IX Corps comprised the British [[10th Division (British)|10th (Irish)]] and [[11th Division (British)|11th Divisions]]. At the time of the landing on 6 August the British were confronted by three Ottoman battalions under the command of a [[Bavaria]]n [[cavalry]] officer, [[Major]] [[Wilhelm Willmer]] whose task was to delay the British until reinforcements could arrive from Bulair, {{convert|30|mi|km}} away.\n\nStopford, who had decided to command the landings from [[Acacia-class sloop|HMS ''Jonquil'']] that was anchored offshore, slept during the attack instead.<ref>[http://www.firstworldwar.com/bio/stopford.htm Biography at firstworldwar.com]</ref> The 11th Division landed on the night of 6 August and two brigades of the 10th Division landed the following morning. The landings, made in the dark without the aid of reliable [[reconnaissance]], suffered from the same confusion that reigned at [[landing at Anzac Cove|Anzac landing]] on 25 April. Lighters ran aground on sandbars so that the troops had to wade some distance to get ashore. Many units became intermingled and officers were unable to locate their objectives. [[Lala Baba]] was captured by the 6th Battalion of the [[Green Howards|Yorkshire Regiment]] in what was the first combat action by any unit of the [[Kitchener's Army|New Army]] of [[Horatio Kitchener, 1st Earl Kitchener of Khartoum|Lord Kitchener]]. The original objectives were the capture of the ridge lines to the north (Kiretch Tepe) and east (Tekke Tepe) and the line of hills to the south on the Anafarta Spur. Stopford's 'caution' and Hamilton's failure to exert his will on his subordinate commanders, meant the objectives were diluted to little more than securing the beach.\n\nBy evening on 7 August, with the [[chain of command]] breaking down, progress had become minimal. Mostly due to Stopford still \"commanding\" from offshore, however, a lack of supplies, especially drinking water, weren't helping matters. To the south east Chocolate Hill and Green Hill were taken in the evening with minimal resistance but constant harassment by [[Shrapnel shell|shrapnel]] and [[sniper]] fire. The British suffered {{nowrap|1,700 casualties}} on the first day at Suvla.\n\nGeneral Sanders was incensed at commander of the 7th and 12th divisions, Colonel Fevzi Bey, for not taking advantage of the Allied disarray at Suvla and pounce on them before they got organized. Turks not expecting a major landing at Suvla had to rush in the two divisions and Fevzi Bey dreaded night attacks, which were rarely successful.<ref>\"Dirilis\", Turgut Ozakman, Bilgi Yayinevi, 2018, pp. 440\u2013470</ref> Sanders relieved Fevzi Bey immediately and gave the responsibility to [[Mustafa Kemal]] who was the commander of the 19th division. Basically he was given the command of a whole group responsible for the front from Anzac Cove to [[Gulf of Saros|Saros]]. He immediately planned for an attack along the Anafarta Hills. Given his success at Ariburnu earlier in spring, Mustafa Kemal's arrival boosted the Ottoman morale.\n\nThe first serious Allied attempt at the ridges of the Anafarta Hills to the east was made on the night of 8 August, following intervention from Hamilton but on the morning of 9 August, the Ottoman reinforcements had begun to arrive and the British were driven back. The fighting concentrated around [[Scimitar Hill]] which protruded northwards from the Anafarta Spur and dominated the southern approach to the Tekke Tepe ridge. Scimitar Hill had been captured then abandoned on 8 August; attempts to retake the hill on 9 and 10 August, were thwarted by the Ottomans. The gunfire was so intense it set the undergrowth ablaze and many of the wounded were incinerated where they lay.\n\nAs the fighting developed, the landing was reinforced by the arrival of the British [[53rd Division (British)|53rd Division]] on 9 August, followed by the [[54th Division (British)|54th Division]] on 10 August.  Stopford now had four divisions under his corps command but was faced by a similar strength of Ottoman defenders. The 53rd Division was mauled in another attack on Scimitar Hill on 10 August.\n\nOn 15 August, Hamilton sacked Stopford and a number of division and brigade commanders. The command of IX Corps was given to Major-General [[Beauvoir De Lisle]], commander of the [[British 29th Division|29th Division]] until Lieutenant-General [[Julian H.G. Byng, 1st Viscount Byng of Vimy|Julian Byng]] could travel from France to assume command.\n\n== Aftermath ==\n\n===Analysis===\n[[File:Southern Trench in Lone Pine, Gallipoli, 8 August 1915 (Graphic Content) (17797424431).jpg|alt=Southern Trench in Lone Pine, Gallipoli, 8 August 1915|thumb|Southern Trench in Lone Pine, Gallipoli, 8 August 1915]]\nOnce the battles of 21 August had finished, the front lines at Suvla and Anzac remained static for the remainder of the campaign. Localised fighting continued but no more major advances were attempted. Many soldiers suffered or perished due to the hostile conditions they endured as a result of their poor preparation and training. Disease transmitted by mosquitoes and the lack of fresh water and shelter hampered the efforts of the division as the men were too weak to fight to their best ability. The insufficient knowledge had an impact of their advancement as their enemy were more familiar to the terrain and could ambush the division successfully. A combination of factors caused their success to be mixed.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Tenth (Irish) Division in Gallipoli|last=1884\u20131930.|first=Cooper, Bryan|date=1993|publisher=Irish Academic Press|isbn=0716525178|location=Dublin, Ireland|oclc=29797013}}</ref>\n\n===Subsequent operations===\n{{main|Battle of Scimitar Hill|Battle of Hill 60 (Gallipoli)}}\n\nAs the shape of the new front line firmed, General Hamilton planned one further attack to try to link the Suvla landing to Anzac. This required the capture of a group of hills; Scimitar Hill and the 'W' Hills from Suvla and Hill 60 from the new Anzac sector. The attacks were to commence on 21 August. At Suvla, de Lisle had his 29th Division and the [[2nd Mounted Division]] which had been moved to Suvla as additional reinforcements.\n\nThe 29th Division was to attack [[Battle of Scimitar Hill|Scimitar Hill]] while the 11th Division was to take the W Hills on the south of the Anafarta Spur. The 2nd Mounted Division was in reserve near Lala Baba on the far side of the salt lake. This attack was the largest mounted by the Allies at Gallipoli. Scimitar Hill was captured briefly but the attackers were driven off or killed by the defensive fire from the Ottomans higher up the spur. Once again the undergrowth ignited, burning many of the wounded. The 2nd Mounted Division were called to join the attack and advanced, marching in extended formation, straight across the salt lake, under fire the whole way. For a second time the hill was captured, briefly, before being lost for the final time.  The attack of the 11th Division towards the W Hills was held up by strong Ottoman defences.\n\nIn the Anzac sector, Hill 60 had been unoccupied on the morning of 7 August, when [[Military history of Australia during World War I|Australian]] scouts passed across but the Ottomans swiftly occupied and fortified the hill. The [[Battle of Hill 60 (Gallipoli)|Battle of Hill 60]] lasted for eight days and while the summit was eventually reached, the Allies were unable to completely dislodge the sacrificially fighting Ottoman defenders.\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |ref=\n|series=History of the Great War Based on Official Documents by Direction of the Historical Section of the Committee of Imperial Defence |title=Military Operations Gallipoli: Inception of the Campaign to May 1915 |volume=I |last=Aspinall-Oglander |first=C. F. | authorlink= |year=1929 |publisher=Heinemann|location=London| edition= |oclc=464479053}}\n* {{cite book |ref=\n|series=History of the Great War Based on Official Documents by Direction of the Historical Section of the Committee of Imperial Defence |title=Military Operations Gallipoli: May 1915 to the Evacuation |volume=II |last=Aspinall-Oglander |first=C. F. |authorlink= |year=1932 |publisher=Heinemann|location=London| edition=IWM & Battery Press 1992 |isbn=0-89839-175-X}}\n* {{cite book |ref=\n|url=https://www.awm.gov.au/collection/RCDIG1069750/|title=The Story of ANZAC from the Outbreak of War to the End of the First Phase of the Gallipoli Campaign, May 4, 1915 | year=1921 |first=C. E. W. |last=Bean |location=Sydney |publisher=Angus and Robertson |series=[[Official History of Australia in the War of 1914\u20131918]] |edition=11th, 1941 |volume=I |oclc=220878987}}\n* {{cite book |ref=harv\n|url=https://www.awm.gov.au/collection/RCDIG1069751/|title=The Story of Anzac from 4 May 1915, to the Evacuation of the Gallipoli Peninsula |volume=II |series=Official History of Australia in the War of 1914\u20131918 |year=1941 |origyear=1921 |first=C. E. W. |last=Bean |authorlink=Charles Bean |edition=11th |location=Canberra |publisher=Australian War Memorial |oclc=39157087}}\n* {{Cite book |ref={{harvid|Cameron|2009}}|title='Sorry, lads, but the order is to go' : the August Offensive, Gallipoli : 1915 |last=Cameron |first=David W. |date=2009 |publisher=UNSW Press |isbn=9781742230788 |location=Sydney, Australia |oclc=647917261}}\n*{{cite book|last=Carlyon|first=Les|title=Gallipoli|year=2002|publisher=Picador Australia|location=|isbn=0732911281|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |ref=\n|title=The Tenth (Irish) Division in Gallipoli |last=Cooper |first=B. |year=1918 |publisher=Herbert Jenkins |location=London |edition=1st |url=https://archive.org/details/tenthirishdivisi00cooprich |accessdate=7 August 2014 |oclc=253010093}}\n* {{cite book |ref=\n|title=The Story of the 29th Division, A Record of Gallant Deeds |last=Gillon |first=S. |authorlink= |year=1925 |publisher=Thomas Nelson |location=London |edition=N & M Press 2002 |isbn=1-84342-265-4}}\n* {{cite book |ref=\n|title=Gallipoli Diary |volume=I |last=Hamilton |first=I. S. M. |year=1920 |publisher=Edward Arnold |location=London |edition= |url=https://archive.org/details/cu31924088057215 |accessdate=7 August 2014 |oclc=816494856}}\n* {{cite book |ref=\n|title=Gallipoli Diary |volume=II |last=Hamilton |first=I. S. M. |year=1920 |publisher=Edward Arnold |location=London |edition= |url=https://archive.org/details/cu31924088057223 |accessdate=7 August 2014 |oclc=816494856}}\n* {{cite book |ref=\n|last=Sanders |first=O. V. K. Liman von |authorlink=Otto Liman von Sanders |title=F\u00fcnf Jahre T\u00fcrkei |trans-title=Five Years in Turkey |year=1919 |language=German |publisher=Scherl |location=Berlin |edition=1st |url=https://archive.org/details/fnfjahretrke00limauoft |accessdate=7 August 2014 |oclc=69108964}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{portal|World War I}}\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{Cite book|last= Chambers|first=Stephen\n|title=Anzac: Sari Bair |publisher = Pen & Sword Military|date=2014|isbn =9781781591901 |oclc=882892566}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Haythornthwaite|first=Philip J. \n|title=Gallipoli, 1915: Frontal Assault on Turkey |publisher =Osprey |date=1991|isbn = 1855321114|oclc=28115553}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Prior |first=Robin |title=Gallipoli: The End of the Myth |publisher=Yale University Press |date=2009 |isbn=9780300149951 |oclc=263409075 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/gallipoliendofmy00robi }}\n*{{Cite book|last=Stanley |first=Peter\n|title=Die in battle, do not despair: the Indians on Gallipoli, 1915 |publisher =Helion & Company Limited |date=2015|isbn =9781910294673 |oclc=898163549}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{coord missing|Turkey}}\n\n{{World War I}}\n{{Ottoman battles in the 20th century}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sari Bair}}\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1915]]\n[[Category:Battles of World War I involving Australia]]\n[[Category:Battles of the Gallipoli Campaign]]\n[[Category:Battles of World War I involving British India]]\n[[Category:Battles of World War I involving New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Battles of World War I involving the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:Battles of World War I involving the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Mustafa Kemal Atat\u00fcrk]]\n[[Category:History of \u00c7anakkale]]\n[[Category:1915 in the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:August 1915 events]]\n", "name_user": "Keith D", "label": "safe", "comment": "De-cap", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Sari_Bair"}
{"title_page": "William Robert Hay", "text_new": "[[File:William Robert Hay Reynolds.png|thumb|William Robert Hay, 1837 engraving]]\n'''William Robert Hay''' (1761\u20131839) was a British barrister, cleric and magistrate, one of the Manchester group associated with the [[Peterloo Massacre]].\n\n==Early life==\nHe was the son of Edward Hay, a diplomat and [[Governor of Barbados]], and his wife Mary Flower, and grandson of [[George Hay, 8th Earl of Kinnoull]]. Born in Portugal, he was sent when young to England, and was brought up for some years by Archbishop [[Robert Hay Drummond]], his uncle. He was on good terms with [[Robert Hay-Drummond, 10th Earl of Kinnoull|Robert]], the archbishop's eldest son, and was sent to [[Westminster School]] with his older brother Thomas.<ref name=\"Raines\">{{cite book |last1=Raines |first1=Francis Robert |last2=Howorth |first2=Henry Hoyle |title=The vicars of Rochdale |date=1883 |publisher=Printed for the Chetham Society |location=Manchester |pages=284-285 |url=https://archive.org/details/vicarsrochdale02raingoog/page/n94/mode/2up}}</ref> He matriculated at [[Christ Church, Oxford]] in December 1776, six months after Thomas and at age 15, graduating B.A. 1780 and M.A. in 1783.<ref>{{alox2|title=Hay, William Robert}}</ref><ref>{{alox2|title=Hay, Thomas (2)}}</ref>\n\nHay entered the [[Inner Temple]] in 1781, and was [[called to the bar]] in 1788. He then went the [[northern circuit]]. He had little success as a barrister, but was employed by [[Sir John Parker Mosley, 1st Baronet]] as steward to the Manchester manorial court.<ref name=\"Raines\"/> \n\n==Clerical career==\nPossibly influenced by [[Lewis Bagot]], a connection by marriage, Hay was ordained deacon in 1797, priest in 1798, and was placed at [[Ashton-under-Lyne]].<ref name=\"Raines2\">{{cite book |last1=Raines |first1=Francis Robert |last2=Howorth |first2=Henry Hoyle |title=The Vicars of Rochdale |date=1883 |publisher=Printed for the Chetham Society |location=Manchester |page=286 |url=https://archive.org/details/vicarsrochdale02raingoog/page/n96/mode/2up}}</ref> He was assistant curate at [[Disley]], in 1798.<ref name=\"CCEd\">{{CCEd |type=person |id=86938 |name=Hay, William Robert |year1=1798 |year2=1820 |accessed=1 April 2020 }}</ref> In 1799 he was curate at [[Hollinwood, Greater Manchester|Hollinwood]] for Rev. John Darbey.<ref name=\"CCEd\"/> He lived at [[Dukenfield Lodge]], a property in his wife's family that was owned by Francis Dukinfield Astley.<ref name=\"Raines2\"/><ref>{{cite book |title=The County Palatine Of Chester: 2,2 |date=1810 |publisher=T. Cadell And W. Davies |page=784 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=4T9aAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA784 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1802 [[Charles Bragge]], a family connection, presented Hay to the rectory of [[Ackworth, West Yorkshire]].<ref name=\"Raines3\">{{cite book |last1=Raines |first1=Francis Robert |last2=Howorth |first2=Henry Hoyle |title=The Vicars of Rochdale |date=1883 |publisher=Printed for the Chetham Society |location=Manchester |page=287 |url=https://archive.org/details/vicarsrochdale02raingoog/page/n97/mode/2up}}</ref> In 1806 [[William Markham (bishop)|William Markham]] gave him a prebend in [[York Minster]].<ref name=\"Raines3\"/>\n\n==Magistrate==\nHay in May 1801 was one of the magistrates who dispersed a meeting near [[Saddleworth]]. It was not covert, having been advertised by handbills, despite the [[Seditious Meetings Act 1795]], recently revived. Writing to [[William Cavendish-Bentinck, 3rd Duke of Portland]], the [[Home Secretary]], Hay reported that the meeting had been peaceful, the magistrates had had no specific intelligence, and seditious intent would be hard to prove.<ref>J. R. Dinwiddy, ''The \"Black Lamp\" in Yorkshire 1801-1802'', Past & Present No. 64 (Aug., 1974), pp. 113\u2013123, at pp. 121\u2013123. Published by: Oxford University Press on behalf of The Past and Present Society {{jstor|650320}}</ref> Later that month, as part of the same campaign of 1800\u20131 to close down public expression of disaffection on the border between Lancashire and Yorkshire, Hay with another magistrate dispersed another meeting near [[Buckton Castle|Buckton]]. Hay's comment to the Home Office stated again that the meeting was peaceful and seditious intent would be hard to establish; but argued expediency.<ref>Frank Munger, ''Suppression of Popular Gatherings in England, 1800\u20131830'', The American Journal of Legal History\nVol. 25, No. 2 (Apr., 1981), pp. 111\u2013140, at p. 134. Published by: Oxford University Press {{jstor|844630}}</ref>\n\nIn 1803 Hay was elected chairman of the quarter sessions for [[Salford Hundred]], succeeding [[Thomas Butterworth Bayley]], who had died in 1802; at this point he had been a [[justice of the peace]] in the [[West Riding of Yorkshire]], [[Lancashire]] and [[Cheshire]] for some years. Salford Hundred, one of the four traditional divisions of Lancashire, was centered on Manchester.<ref name=\"Raines3\"/><ref>{{cite book |last1=Navickas |first1=Katrina |title=Loyalism and Radicalism in Lancashire, 1798-1815 |date=2009 |publisher=OUP Oxford |isbn=978-0-19-955967-1 |page=120 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=0xYUDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA120 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Taylor |first1=Peter |title=Quarter sessions in Lancashire in the middle of the eighteenth century: the court in session and its records |journal=Journal of the Historic Society of Lancashire and Cheshire. |date=1989 |volume=139 |url=https://www.hslc.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/139-4-Taylor.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite DNB|wstitle=Bayley, Thomas Butterworth|volume=3}}</ref><ref name=\"GM\">{{cite book |title=The Gentleman's Magazine |date=1840 |publisher=W. Pickering |pages=95-96 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=TCVIAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA95 |language=en}}</ref> Bayley, Hay and [[Thomas Bancroft (priest)|Thomas Bancroft]], vicar of [[Bolton]], formed a discriminating group gathering local intelligence and showing scepticism to claims of their spies and informants, whom they recruited carefully. Their attitude differed from other, more credulous magistrates.<ref>Alan Booth, ''The United Englishmen and Radical Politics in the Industrial North-West of England, 1795\u20131803'', International Review of Social History Vol. 31, No. 3 (1986), pp. 271\u2013297, at p. 272. Published by: Cambridge University Press {{jstor|44582816}}</ref>\n\nIn 1818 Hay was deprecating to [[Henry Hobhouse]] of the Home Office the reluctance of manufacturers to use the [[Combination acts]] against strikers in the cotton industry who were attacking factories, putting it down to fear.<ref>James R. Cuca, ''Industrial Change and the Progress of Labor in the English Cotton Industry'', International Review of Social History Vol. 22, No. 2 (1977), pp. 241\u2013255, at p. 247. Published by: Cambridge University Press {{jstor|44581773}}</ref> In January 1819, Hay was called out in the series \"Letters to the Treason-Hunting Municipality of Manchester\" appearing in the ''[[Manchester Observer]]'', by the radical printer William Ogden: \"As a magistrate, you have taken an active part in committing to prison a great number of not only ''innocent'' but ''worthy'' men\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Poole |first1=Robert |title=Peterloo: The English Uprising |date=2019 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-108620-5 |page=22 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=rdShDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA202 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Chetham Society |first1=Manchester |title=Remains, historical and literary, connected with the palatine counties of Lancaster and Chester. New ser |date=1883 |publisher=Manchester |page=288 |url=https://archive.org/details/remainshistornew02chetuoft/page/288/mode/2up}}</ref> In July 1819 Hay warned a [[grand jury#England and Wales|grand jury]] that the [[Symbolism in the French Revolution#Liberty cap|cap of liberty]] associated with the [[French Revolution]] was being displayed at radical meetings.<ref>James Epstein, ''Understanding the Cap of Liberty: Symbolic Practice and Social Conflict in Early Nineteenth-Century England'', Past & Present No. 122 (Feb., 1989), pp. 75\u2013118, at p. 79. Published by: Oxford University Press on behalf of The Past and Present Society {{jstor|650952}}</ref>\n\nPresent as a magistrate on 16 August 1819 at [[Peterloo]], Hay wrote the letter of that evening to [[Lord Sidmouth]] giving an account of the events, [[James Norris (lawyer)|James Norris]] being \"very much fatigued by the harrassing duty of this day\". He included the reading of the [[Riot Act]], and the arrests of [[Henry Hunt (politician)|Henry Hunt]] and [[Joseph Johnson]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Raines |first1=Francis Robert |last2=Howorth |first2=Henry Hoyle |title=The Vicars of Rochdale |date=1883 |publisher=Printed for the Chetham Society |location=Manchester |page=291 |url=https://archive.org/details/vicarsrochdale02raingoog/page/n102/mode/2up}}</ref> In the film ''[[Peterloo (film)|Peterloo]]'' by [[Mike Leigh]], Hay is played by [[Jeff Rawle]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Peterloo (2018) - IMDb |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt4614612/fullcredits}}</ref>\n\nIn October 1819, Hay attended a dinner given by [[Lord Liverpool]], the Prime Minister, where he was treated with high regard by [[Sir John Copley]], the [[Solicitor General for England and Wales|Solicitor General]]. The [[Seditious Meetings Act 1819]] of December reportedly owes clauses to suggestions made by Hay to Copley.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Raines |first1=Francis Robert |last2=Howorth |first2=Henry Hoyle |title=The Vicars of Rochdale |date=1883 |publisher=Printed for the Chetham Society |location=Manchester |page=294 note |url=https://archive.org/details/vicarsrochdale02raingoog/page/n104/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\n==Later life==\nHay was created vicar of [[Rochdale]] on 3 January 1820.<ref name=\"CCEd\"/> The Rochdale incumbent Thomas Drake (1745\u20131819) had died in September.<ref>{{acad|id=DRK764T|name=Drake, Thomas}}</ref> He had ordered volunteer troops to fire on a crowd during a 1795 riot, causing two deaths, and his reputation had suffered.<ref>Alan Booth, ''Food Riots in the North-West of England 1790\u20131801'', Past & Present No. 77 (Nov., 1977), pp. 84\u2013107, at p. 100. Published by: Oxford University Press on behalf of The Past and Present Society {{jstor|650388}}</ref> Other candidates for this wealthy living were [[Thomas Dunham Whitaker]], and [[George D'Oyly]] who had better prospects elsewhere at [[Lambeth]]. Hay was successful with the backing of the Manchester municipal establishment.<ref name=\"Raines3\"/><ref>{{cite book |last1=Raines |first1=Francis Robert |last2=Howorth |first2=Henry H. (Henry Hoyle) |title=The Vicars of Rochdale |date=1883 |publisher=Printed for the Chetham Society |location=Manchester |pages=295-296 |url=https://archive.org/details/vicarsrochdale02raingoog/page/n106/mode/2up}}</ref> Hay continued to hold the Ackworth rectory with  a dispensation;<ref>{{cite web |title=Dispensation Record CCEd Record ID: 11819 Linked to person: Hay, William Robert 1797-1820 |url=https://theclergydatabase.org.uk/jsp/DisplayDispensation.jsp?CDBDispenID=11819}}</ref> he had curates there, William James Farrington (1820), John Hope (1821), Richard Bassnett (1823), and Thomas Frederick Paull Hankins (1828).<ref>{{CCEd |type=location |id=21296 |name=Parish (Church): Ackworth |accessed=3 April 2020 }}</ref> At Rochdale also he had curates, beginning with [[James Aspinall]] (1824), and including [[Francis Robert Raines]] (1829\u20131832).<ref>{{CCEd |type=location |id=5667 |name=Parish (Church): Rochdale |accessed=3 April 2020 }}</ref> Raines wrote \"Mr. Hay seems never to have been known in his parish as a clergyman, but only as a lawyer and a politician.\"<ref>{{cite book |last1=Raines |first1=Francis Robert |last2=Howorth |first2=Henry Hoyle |title=The Vicars of Rochdale |date=1883 |publisher=Printed for the Chetham Society |location=Manchester |page=306 |url=https://archive.org/details/vicarsrochdale02raingoog/page/n116/mode/2up}}</ref> [[Henry Charles Beeching]] in the ''[[Dictionary of National Biography]]'' called Hay an absentee [[Erastian]].<ref>{{cite DNB|wstitle=Molesworth, John Edward Nassau|volume=38}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 1820s the legal issues raised by Peterloo were still live, and the legal doctrine of [[unlawful assembly]] was still being worked out through case law. Hay was cross-examined in ''Redford v Birley'' (1822), before [[George Sowley Holroyd]]. On the question of at what point the Peterloo assembly became illegal, Hay stated:\n\n<blockquote>I will explain what I mean by tumultuous; that sort of meeting I consider illegal, and a breach of the peace, either in point of common sense, or according to legal authorities.<ref>Michael Lobban, ''From Seditious Libel to Unlawful Assembly: Peterloo and the Changing Face of Political Crime c.1770\u20131820'', Oxford Journal of Legal Studies Vol. 10, No. 3 (Autumn, 1990), pp. 307\u2013352, at p. 342 and p. 347. Published by: Oxford University Press {{jstor|764345}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nHay gave up his position as chairman of the Salford Quarter Sessions in 1823, and was seriously ill in 1824.<ref name=\"Raines3\"/> He was replaced as chairman by [[Thomas Starkie]], and then in 1825 by [[James Norris (lawyer)|James Norris]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Baines |first1=Edward |title=History, Directory, and Gazetteer, of the County Palatine of Lancaster: With a Variety of Commercial & Statistical Information ... Illustrated by Maps and Plans |date=1825 |publisher=W. Wales & Company |page=153 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=pIAfAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA153 |language=en}}</ref> He was briefly back in court in 1825, and not in a good temper, after Starkie resigned, for a [[right of way]] case involving the magistrate Ralph Wright, at [[Flixton, Greater Manchester|Flixton]].<ref>''Trial, at the Salford Michaelmas Sessions, 1827, of appeals against orders of two magistrates for stopping up footways, in the parish of Flixton'', 1827, at p. 6. {{jstor|60238116}}</ref>\n\nAt Rochdale, Hay was still active in local politics in the last summer of his life, extending the hustings on a vote affecting [[church rates]].<ref>Eileen Yeo, ''Christianity in Chartist Struggle 1838\u20131842'', Past & Present No. 91 (May, 1981), pp. 109\u2013139, at p. 128. Published by: Oxford University Press on behalf of The Past and Present Society {{jstor|650520}}</ref> The church rate issue in Rochdale had been vexed for nearly a generation. Jacob Bright, father of [[John Bright]], had refused to pay it over 20 times, from 1811 to 1833.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Trevelyan |first1=George Macaulay |title=The Life of John Bright |date=1913 |publisher=London : Constable & Co. Ltd. |page=36 |url=https://archive.org/details/lifeofjohnbright00trev/page/36/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\nHay died on 10 December 1839, at Ackworth rectory. His obituary in the ''[[Gentleman's Magazine]]'' compared Hay's role at Peterloo with that of [[Thomas Phillips (mayor)|Sir Thomas Phillips]] in the recent [[Newport Rising]].<ref name=\"GM\"/> He was succeeded at Rochdale by [[John Edward Nassau Molesworth]];<ref>{{alox2|title=Molesworth, John (Edward Nassau)}}</ref> and at Arkworth by Edmund Goodenough Bayly.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Foster |first1=Joseph |title=Index Ecclesiasticus: or, Alphabetical lists of all ecclesiastical dignitaries in England and Wales since the reformation |date=1890 |publisher=Dalcassian Publishing Company |page=11 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=K1THDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA11 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{alox2|title=Bayly, Rev. Edmund Goodenough}}</ref>\n\n==Collector==\nMuch material collected by Hay was added to scrapbooks. Manuscripts, [[commonplace book]]s and scrapbooks (18 volumes) went to [[Chetham's Library]]. Other manuscripts came into the hands of [[A. P. Wadsworth]], whose daughter Janet gave them in 1957 to the [[John Rylands Library]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Walmsley |first1=Robert |title=Peterloo, the case re-opened |publisher=Manchester University Press |page=563 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=HRANAQAAIAAJ&pg=RA1-PA563 |language=en}}</ref> These scrapbooks, mostly consisting of newspaper cuttings, are in some ways comparable with those of the Yorkshire antiquarian and diarist Dorothy Richardson (1748\u20131819). Hay's interests included poetry, trivia and the local volunteer corps. The scrapbooks were maintained in parallel with commonplace books.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kinsley |first1=Zoe |title=Cutting and Pasting the Popular Press: The Scrapbooks of Dorothy Richardson (1748-1819) |journal=Bulletin of the John Rylands Library, |date=2019 |volume=96 |issue=96 (1). |url=http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:JrHKNXrQdBoJ:hira.hope.ac.uk/id/eprint/2981/1/Kinsley%2520Cutting%2520and%2520Pasting%2520-%2520HIRA.pdf+&cd=1&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=uk}}</ref> The scrapbooks and other papers were given by Hay's daughter Mary, after his death, to Francis Robert Raines.<ref name=\"Raines314\">{{cite book |last1=Raines |first1=Francis Robert |last2=Howorth |first2=Henry Hoyle |title=The Vicars of Rochdale |date=1883 |publisher=Printed for the Chetham Society |location=Manchester |pages=314\u2013315 |url=https://archive.org/details/vicarsrochdale02raingoog/page/n124/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\nHay had a numismatic collection.<ref>{{cite book |title=The British Numismatic Journal: Including the Proceedings of the British Numismatic Society |date=2002 |publisher=British Numismatic Society |page=120 |language=en}}</ref> Many items in it came from friends including [[Sarah Sophia Banks]], with whom he shared interests such as [[token coin]]s and [[ephemera]].<ref name=\"Raines314\"/> Hay annotated contemporary numismatic catalogues, the ''Correct and Complete Representation of All the Provincial Copper Coins, Tokens of Trade, and Cards of Address'' by [[Charles Pye senior]], and ''The Virtuoso's Companion and Coin Collectors Guide'' (2 vols.) by Thomas Prattent, and a ''List of Provincial Copper Coins or Tokens'' by Samuel Birchall.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hamer |first1=Samuel Henry |title=Notes on Some Interesting Token Books and their Original Owner |journal=The Numismatist |date=1905-1906 |volume=18-19 |page=18 |url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015039767754&view=1up&seq=412 |language=en}}</ref> Hay's method has been identified as a species of [[Grangerisation]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Seaby's Coin and Medal Bulletin |date=1976 |publisher=B.A. Seaby Limited |page=425|issue=689-700 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=1hAaAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA425 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nA collection of books of Puritan sermons went on Hay's death to Alexander Barclay, the bookseller at [[York]]. A large trunk of papers went to Hay's brother Thomas. He left two libraries, at Ackworth and Rochdale, and paintings including a portrait by [[Godfrey Kneller]] of his paternal grandmother Abigail Harley, daughter of [[Robert Harley, 1st Earl of Oxford and Earl Mortimer]].<ref name=\"Raines314\"/>\n\n==Family==\nHay married in 1793 Mary Wagstaffe, widow of [[John Astley (painter)|John Astley]], daughter of William Wagstaffe.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lodge |first1=Edmund |title=The Peerage of the British Empire, as at Present Existing, Arranged and Printed from the Personal Communications of the Nobility |date=1832 |publisher=Saunders and Otley |page=237 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=IIsUAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA237 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/search?keyword=Hay%2C%20William%20Robert%2C%201761-1839&page=1 William Robert Hay at Manchester Digital Collections]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hay, William Robert}}\n[[Category:1761 births]]\n[[Category:1839 deaths]]\n[[Category:British Anglican priests]]\n[[Category:British barristers]]\n[[Category:Magistrates]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:William Robert Hay Reynolds.png|thumb|William Robert Hay, 1837 engraving]]\n'''William Robert Hay''' (1761\u20131839) was a British barrister, cleric and magistrate, one of the Manchester group associated with the [[Peterloo Massacre]].\n\n==Early life==\nHe was the son of Edward Hay, a diplomat and [[Governor of Barbados]], and his wife Mary Flower, and grandson of [[George Hay, 8th Earl of Kinnoull]]. Born in Portugal, he was sent when young to England, and was brought up for some years by Archbishop [[Robert Hay Drummond]], his uncle. He was on good terms with [[Robert Hay-Drummond, 10th Earl of Kinnoull|Robert]], the archbishop's eldest son, and was sent to [[Westminster School]] with his older brother Thomas.<ref name=\"Raines\">{{cite book |last1=Raines |first1=Francis Robert |last2=Howorth |first2=Henry Hoyle |title=The vicars of Rochdale |date=1883 |publisher=Printed for the Chetham Society |location=Manchester |pages=284-285 |url=https://archive.org/details/vicarsrochdale02raingoog/page/n94/mode/2up}}</ref> He matriculated at [[Christ Church, Oxford]] in December 1776, six months after Thomas and at age 15, graduating B.A. 1780 and M.A. in 1783.<ref>{{alox2|title=Hay, William Robert}}</ref><ref>{{alox2|title=Hay, Thomas (2)}}</ref>\n\nHay entered the [[Inner Temple]] in 1781, and was [[called to the bar]] in 1788. He then went the [[northern circuit]]. He had little success as a barrister, but was employed by [[Sir John Parker Mosley, 1st Baronet]] as steward to the Manchester manorial court.<ref name=\"Raines\"/> \n\n==Clerical career==\nPossibly influenced by [[Lewis Bagot]], a connection by marriage, Hay was ordained deacon in 1797, priest in 1798, and was placed at [[Ashton-under-Lyne]].<ref name=\"Raines2\">{{cite book |last1=Raines |first1=Francis Robert |last2=Howorth |first2=Henry Hoyle |title=The Vicars of Rochdale |date=1883 |publisher=Printed for the Chetham Society |location=Manchester |page=286 |url=https://archive.org/details/vicarsrochdale02raingoog/page/n96/mode/2up}}</ref> He was assistant curate at [[Disley]], in 1798.<ref name=\"CCEd\">{{CCEd |type=person |id=86938 |name=Hay, William Robert |year1=1798 |year2=1820 |accessed=1 April 2020 }}</ref> In 1799 he was curate at [[Hollinwood, Greater Manchester|Hollinwood]] for Rev. John Darbey.<ref name=\"CCEd\"/> He lived at [[Dukenfield Lodge]], a property in his wife's family that was owned by Francis Dukinfield Astley.<ref name=\"Raines2\"/><ref>{{cite book |title=The County Palatine Of Chester: 2,2 |date=1810 |publisher=T. Cadell And W. Davies |page=784 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=4T9aAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA784 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1802 [[Charles Bragge]], a family connection, presented Hay to the rectory of [[Ackworth, West Yorkshire]].<ref name=\"Raines3\">{{cite book |last1=Raines |first1=Francis Robert |last2=Howorth |first2=Henry Hoyle |title=The Vicars of Rochdale |date=1883 |publisher=Printed for the Chetham Society |location=Manchester |page=287 |url=https://archive.org/details/vicarsrochdale02raingoog/page/n97/mode/2up}}</ref> In 1806 [[William Markham (bishop)|William Markham]] gave him a prebend in [[York Minster]].<ref name=\"Raines3\"/>\n\n==Magistrate==\nHay in May 1801 was one of the magistrates who dispersed a meeting near [[Saddleworth]]. It was not covert, having been advertised by handbills, despite the [[Seditious Meetings Act 1795]], recently revived. Writing to [[William Cavendish-Bentinck, 3rd Duke of Portland]], the [[Home Secretary]], Hay reported that the meeting had been peaceful, the magistrates had had no specific intelligence, and seditious intent would be hard to prove.<ref>J. R. Dinwiddy, ''The \"Black Lamp\" in Yorkshire 1801-1802'', Past & Present No. 64 (Aug., 1974), pp. 113\u2013123, at pp. 121\u2013123. Published by: Oxford University Press on behalf of The Past and Present Society {{jstor|650320}}</ref> Later that month, as part of the same campaign of 1800\u20131 to close down public expression of disaffection on the border between Lancashire and Yorkshire, Hay with another magistrate dispersed another meeting near [[Buckton Castle|Buckton]]. Hay's comment to the Home Office stated again that the meeting was peaceful and seditious intent would be hard to establish; but argued expediency.<ref>Frank Munger, ''Suppression of Popular Gatherings in England, 1800\u20131830'', The American Journal of Legal History\nVol. 25, No. 2 (Apr., 1981), pp. 111\u2013140, at p. 134. Published by: Oxford University Press {{jstor|844630}}</ref>\n\nIn 1803 Hay was elected chairman of the quarter sessions for [[Salford Hundred]], succeeding [[Thomas Butterworth Bayley]], who had died in 1802; at this point he had been a [[justice of the peace]] in the [[West Riding of Yorkshire]], [[Lancashire]] and [[Cheshire]] for some years. Salford Hundred, one of the four traditional divisions of Lancashire, was centered on Manchester.<ref name=\"Raines3\"/><ref>{{cite book |last1=Navickas |first1=Katrina |title=Loyalism and Radicalism in Lancashire, 1798-1815 |date=2009 |publisher=OUP Oxford |isbn=978-0-19-955967-1 |page=120 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=0xYUDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA120 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Taylor |first1=Peter |title=Quarter sessions in Lancashire in the middle of the eighteenth century: the court in session and its records |journal=Journal of the Historic Society of Lancashire and Cheshire. |date=1989 |volume=139 |url=https://www.hslc.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/139-4-Taylor.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite DNB|wstitle=Bayley, Thomas Butterworth|volume=3}}</ref><ref name=\"GM\">{{cite book |title=The Gentleman's Magazine |date=1840 |publisher=W. Pickering |pages=95-96 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=TCVIAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA95 |language=en}}</ref> Bayley, Hay and [[Thomas Bancroft (priest)|Thomas Bancroft]], vicar of [[Bolton]], formed a discriminating group gathering local intelligence and showing scepticism to claims of their spies and informants, whom they recruited carefully. Their attitude differed from other, more credulous magistrates.<ref>Alan Booth, ''The United Englishmen and Radical Politics in the Industrial North-West of England, 1795\u20131803'', International Review of Social History Vol. 31, No. 3 (1986), pp. 271\u2013297, at p. 272. Published by: Cambridge University Press {{jstor|44582816}}</ref>\n\nIn 1818 Hay was deprecating to [[Henry Hobhouse]] of the Home Office the reluctance of manufacturers to use the [[Combination acts]] against strikers in the cotton industry who were attacking factories, putting it down to fear.<ref>James R. Cuca, ''Industrial Change and the Progress of Labor in the English Cotton Industry'', International Review of Social History Vol. 22, No. 2 (1977), pp. 241\u2013255, at p. 247. Published by: Cambridge University Press {{jstor|44581773}}</ref> In January 1819, Hay was called out in the series \"Letters to the Treason-Hunting Municipality of Manchester\" appearing in the ''[[Manchester Observer]]'', by the radical printer William Ogden: \"As a magistrate, you have taken an active part in committing to prison a great number of not only ''innocent'' but ''worthy'' men\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Poole |first1=Robert |title=Peterloo: The English Uprising |date=2019 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-108620-5 |page=22 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=rdShDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA202 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Chetham Society |first1=Manchester |title=Remains, historical and literary, connected with the palatine counties of Lancaster and Chester. New ser |date=1883 |publisher=Manchester |page=288 |url=https://archive.org/details/remainshistornew02chetuoft/page/288/mode/2up}}</ref> In July 1819 Hay warned a [[grand jury#England and Wales|grand jury]] that the [[Symbolism in the French Revolution#Liberty cap|cap of liberty]] associated with the [[French Revolution]] was being displayed at radical meetings.<ref>James Epstein, ''Understanding the Cap of Liberty: Symbolic Practice and Social Conflict in Early Nineteenth-Century England'', Past & Present No. 122 (Feb., 1989), pp. 75\u2013118, at p. 79. Published by: Oxford University Press on behalf of The Past and Present Society {{jstor|650952}}</ref>\n\nPresent as a magistrate on 16 August 1819 at [[Peterloo]], Hay wrote the letter of that evening to [[Lord Sidmouth]] giving an account of the events, [[James Norris (lawyer)|James Norris]] being \"very much fatigued by the harrassing duty of this day\". He included the reading of the [[Riot Act]], and the arrests of [[Henry Hunt (politician)|Henry Hunt]] and [[Joseph Johnson]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Raines |first1=Francis Robert |last2=Howorth |first2=Henry Hoyle |title=The Vicars of Rochdale |date=1883 |publisher=Printed for the Chetham Society |location=Manchester |page=291 |url=https://archive.org/details/vicarsrochdale02raingoog/page/n102/mode/2up}}</ref> In the film ''[[Peterloo (film)|Peterloo]]'' by [[Mike Leigh]], Ethelston is played by [[Jeff Rawle]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Peterloo (2018) - IMDb |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt4614612/fullcredits}}</ref>\n\nIn October 1819, Hay attended a dinner given by [[Lord Liverpool]], the Prime Minister, where he was treated with high regard by [[Sir John Copley]], the [[Solicitor General for England and Wales|Solicitor General]]. The [[Seditious Meetings Act 1819]] of December reportedly owes clauses to suggestions made by Hay to Copley.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Raines |first1=Francis Robert |last2=Howorth |first2=Henry Hoyle |title=The Vicars of Rochdale |date=1883 |publisher=Printed for the Chetham Society |location=Manchester |page=294 note |url=https://archive.org/details/vicarsrochdale02raingoog/page/n104/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\n==Later life==\nHay was created vicar of [[Rochdale]] on 3 January 1820.<ref name=\"CCEd\"/> The Rochdale incumbent Thomas Drake (1745\u20131819) had died in September.<ref>{{acad|id=DRK764T|name=Drake, Thomas}}</ref> He had ordered volunteer troops to fire on a crowd during a 1795 riot, causing two deaths, and his reputation had suffered.<ref>Alan Booth, ''Food Riots in the North-West of England 1790\u20131801'', Past & Present No. 77 (Nov., 1977), pp. 84\u2013107, at p. 100. Published by: Oxford University Press on behalf of The Past and Present Society {{jstor|650388}}</ref> Other candidates for this wealthy living were [[Thomas Dunham Whitaker]], and [[George D'Oyly]] who had better prospects elsewhere at [[Lambeth]]. Hay was successful with the backing of the Manchester municipal establishment.<ref name=\"Raines3\"/><ref>{{cite book |last1=Raines |first1=Francis Robert |last2=Howorth |first2=Henry H. (Henry Hoyle) |title=The Vicars of Rochdale |date=1883 |publisher=Printed for the Chetham Society |location=Manchester |pages=295-296 |url=https://archive.org/details/vicarsrochdale02raingoog/page/n106/mode/2up}}</ref> Hay continued to hold the Ackworth rectory with  a dispensation;<ref>{{cite web |title=Dispensation Record CCEd Record ID: 11819 Linked to person: Hay, William Robert 1797-1820 |url=https://theclergydatabase.org.uk/jsp/DisplayDispensation.jsp?CDBDispenID=11819}}</ref> he had curates there, William James Farrington (1820), John Hope (1821), Richard Bassnett (1823), and Thomas Frederick Paull Hankins (1828).<ref>{{CCEd |type=location |id=21296 |name=Parish (Church): Ackworth |accessed=3 April 2020 }}</ref> At Rochdale also he had curates, beginning with [[James Aspinall]] (1824), and including [[Francis Robert Raines]] (1829\u20131832).<ref>{{CCEd |type=location |id=5667 |name=Parish (Church): Rochdale |accessed=3 April 2020 }}</ref> Raines wrote \"Mr. Hay seems never to have been known in his parish as a clergyman, but only as a lawyer and a politician.\"<ref>{{cite book |last1=Raines |first1=Francis Robert |last2=Howorth |first2=Henry Hoyle |title=The Vicars of Rochdale |date=1883 |publisher=Printed for the Chetham Society |location=Manchester |page=306 |url=https://archive.org/details/vicarsrochdale02raingoog/page/n116/mode/2up}}</ref> [[Henry Charles Beeching]] in the ''[[Dictionary of National Biography]]'' called Hay an absentee [[Erastian]].<ref>{{cite DNB|wstitle=Molesworth, John Edward Nassau|volume=38}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 1820s the legal issues raised by Peterloo were still live, and the legal doctrine of [[unlawful assembly]] was still being worked out through case law. Hay was cross-examined in ''Redford v Birley'' (1822), before [[George Sowley Holroyd]]. On the question of at what point the Peterloo assembly became illegal, Hay stated:\n\n<blockquote>I will explain what I mean by tumultuous; that sort of meeting I consider illegal, and a breach of the peace, either in point of common sense, or according to legal authorities.<ref>Michael Lobban, ''From Seditious Libel to Unlawful Assembly: Peterloo and the Changing Face of Political Crime c.1770\u20131820'', Oxford Journal of Legal Studies Vol. 10, No. 3 (Autumn, 1990), pp. 307\u2013352, at p. 342 and p. 347. Published by: Oxford University Press {{jstor|764345}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nHay gave up his position as chairman of the Salford Quarter Sessions in 1823, and was seriously ill in 1824.<ref name=\"Raines3\"/> He was replaced as chairman by [[Thomas Starkie]], and then in 1825 by [[James Norris (lawyer)|James Norris]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Baines |first1=Edward |title=History, Directory, and Gazetteer, of the County Palatine of Lancaster: With a Variety of Commercial & Statistical Information ... Illustrated by Maps and Plans |date=1825 |publisher=W. Wales & Company |page=153 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=pIAfAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA153 |language=en}}</ref> He was briefly back in court in 1825, and not in a good temper, after Starkie resigned, for a [[right of way]] case involving the magistrate Ralph Wright, at [[Flixton, Greater Manchester|Flixton]].<ref>''Trial, at the Salford Michaelmas Sessions, 1827, of appeals against orders of two magistrates for stopping up footways, in the parish of Flixton'', 1827, at p. 6. {{jstor|60238116}}</ref>\n\nAt Rochdale, Hay was still active in local politics in the last summer of his life, extending the hustings on a vote affecting [[church rates]].<ref>Eileen Yeo, ''Christianity in Chartist Struggle 1838\u20131842'', Past & Present No. 91 (May, 1981), pp. 109\u2013139, at p. 128. Published by: Oxford University Press on behalf of The Past and Present Society {{jstor|650520}}</ref> The church rate issue in Rochdale had been vexed for nearly a generation. Jacob Bright, father of [[John Bright]], had refused to pay it over 20 times, from 1811 to 1833.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Trevelyan |first1=George Macaulay |title=The Life of John Bright |date=1913 |publisher=London : Constable & Co. Ltd. |page=36 |url=https://archive.org/details/lifeofjohnbright00trev/page/36/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\nHay died on 10 December 1839, at Ackworth rectory. His obituary in the ''[[Gentleman's Magazine]]'' compared Hay's role at Peterloo with that of [[Thomas Phillips (mayor)|Sir Thomas Phillips]] in the recent [[Newport Rising]].<ref name=\"GM\"/> He was succeeded at Rochdale by [[John Edward Nassau Molesworth]];<ref>{{alox2|title=Molesworth, John (Edward Nassau)}}</ref> and at Arkworth by Edmund Goodenough Bayly.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Foster |first1=Joseph |title=Index Ecclesiasticus: or, Alphabetical lists of all ecclesiastical dignitaries in England and Wales since the reformation |date=1890 |publisher=Dalcassian Publishing Company |page=11 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=K1THDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA11 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{alox2|title=Bayly, Rev. Edmund Goodenough}}</ref>\n\n==Collector==\nMuch material collected by Hay was added to scrapbooks. Manuscripts, [[commonplace book]]s and scrapbooks (18 volumes) went to [[Chetham's Library]]. Other manuscripts came into the hands of [[A. P. Wadsworth]], whose daughter Janet gave them in 1957 to the [[John Rylands Library]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Walmsley |first1=Robert |title=Peterloo, the case re-opened |publisher=Manchester University Press |page=563 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=HRANAQAAIAAJ&pg=RA1-PA563 |language=en}}</ref> These scrapbooks, mostly consisting of newspaper cuttings, are in some ways comparable with those of the Yorkshire antiquarian and diarist Dorothy Richardson (1748\u20131819). Hay's interests included poetry, trivia and the local volunteer corps. The scrapbooks were maintained in parallel with commonplace books.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kinsley |first1=Zoe |title=Cutting and Pasting the Popular Press: The Scrapbooks of Dorothy Richardson (1748-1819) |journal=Bulletin of the John Rylands Library, |date=2019 |volume=96 |issue=96 (1). |url=http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:JrHKNXrQdBoJ:hira.hope.ac.uk/id/eprint/2981/1/Kinsley%2520Cutting%2520and%2520Pasting%2520-%2520HIRA.pdf+&cd=1&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=uk}}</ref> The scrapbooks and other papers were given by Hay's daughter Mary, after his death, to Francis Robert Raines.<ref name=\"Raines314\">{{cite book |last1=Raines |first1=Francis Robert |last2=Howorth |first2=Henry Hoyle |title=The Vicars of Rochdale |date=1883 |publisher=Printed for the Chetham Society |location=Manchester |pages=314\u2013315 |url=https://archive.org/details/vicarsrochdale02raingoog/page/n124/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\nHay had a numismatic collection.<ref>{{cite book |title=The British Numismatic Journal: Including the Proceedings of the British Numismatic Society |date=2002 |publisher=British Numismatic Society |page=120 |language=en}}</ref> Many items in it came from friends including [[Sarah Sophia Banks]], with whom he shared interests such as [[token coin]]s and [[ephemera]].<ref name=\"Raines314\"/> Hay annotated contemporary numismatic catalogues, the ''Correct and Complete Representation of All the Provincial Copper Coins, Tokens of Trade, and Cards of Address'' by [[Charles Pye senior]], and ''The Virtuoso's Companion and Coin Collectors Guide'' (2 vols.) by Thomas Prattent, and a ''List of Provincial Copper Coins or Tokens'' by Samuel Birchall.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hamer |first1=Samuel Henry |title=Notes on Some Interesting Token Books and their Original Owner |journal=The Numismatist |date=1905-1906 |volume=18-19 |page=18 |url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015039767754&view=1up&seq=412 |language=en}}</ref> Hay's method has been identified as a species of [[Grangerisation]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Seaby's Coin and Medal Bulletin |date=1976 |publisher=B.A. Seaby Limited |page=425|issue=689-700 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=1hAaAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA425 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nA collection of books of Puritan sermons went on Hay's death to Alexander Barclay, the bookseller at [[York]]. A large trunk of papers went to Hay's brother Thomas. He left two libraries, at Ackworth and Rochdale, and paintings including a portrait by [[Godfrey Kneller]] of his paternal grandmother Abigail Harley, daughter of [[Robert Harley, 1st Earl of Oxford and Earl Mortimer]].<ref name=\"Raines314\"/>\n\n==Family==\nHay married in 1793 Mary Wagstaffe, widow of [[John Astley (painter)|John Astley]], daughter of William Wagstaffe.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lodge |first1=Edmund |title=The Peerage of the British Empire, as at Present Existing, Arranged and Printed from the Personal Communications of the Nobility |date=1832 |publisher=Saunders and Otley |page=237 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=IIsUAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA237 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/search?keyword=Hay%2C%20William%20Robert%2C%201761-1839&page=1 William Robert Hay at Manchester Digital Collections]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hay, William Robert}}\n[[Category:1761 births]]\n[[Category:1839 deaths]]\n[[Category:British Anglican priests]]\n[[Category:British barristers]]\n[[Category:Magistrates]]\n", "name_user": "Charles Matthews", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMagistrate:fx", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Robert_Hay"}
{"title_page": "Vina (department)", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!--See the Table at Infobox Settlement for all fields and descriptions of usage-->\n<!-- Basic info  ---------------->\n|name          = Vina Department\n|other_name             =\n|native_name            =  <!-- for cities whose native name is not in English -->\n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = [[Departments of Cameroon|Department]]\n|motto                  =\n<!-- images and maps  ----------->\n|image_skyline          =\n|imagesize              = \n|image_caption          = \n|image_flag             = \n|flag_size              =\n|image_seal             = \n|seal_size              =\n|image_shield           = \n|shield_size            =\n|image_map              = CM-Vina.png\n|mapsize                = 300px\n|map_caption            = Department location in Cameroon\n|pushpin_map            = Cameroon#Africa<!-- the name of a location map as per http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Location_map -->\n|pushpin_label_position =bottom\n|pushpin_mapsize        = 300\n|pushpin_map_caption    =\n<!-- Location ------------------>\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = {{flag|Cameroon}}\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Regions of Cameroon]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Adamawa Region]]\n|subdivision_type2      = Capital\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Ngaound\u00e9r\u00e9]]\n|subdivision_type3      =\n|subdivision_name3      = \n|<!-- Politics ----------------->\n|government_footnotes   =\n|government_type        =\n|leader_title           =\n|leader_name            =\n|leader_title1          =  <!-- for places with, say, both a mayor and a city manager -->\n|leader_name1           =\n|established_title      =  <!-- Settled -->\n|established_date       = \n<!-- Area    --------------------->\n|area_magnitude         = \n|unit_pref                =Imperial <!--Enter: Imperial, if Imperial (metric) is desired-->\n|area_footnotes           =\n|area_total_km2           =17196 <!-- ALL fields dealing with a measurements are subject to automatic unit conversion-->\n|area_land_km2            = <!--See table @ Template:Infobox Settlement for details on automatic unit conversion-->\n<!-- Population   ----------------------->\n|population_as_of               =2001\n|population_footnotes           =\n|population_note                =\n|population_total               =247,427\n|population_density_km2         =\n|population_density_sq_mi       =\n|population_metro               =\n|population_density_metro_km2   =\n|population_density_metro_sq_mi =\n|population_blank1_title        =Ethnicities\n|population_blank1              =\n|population_density_blank1_km2 =   \n|population_density_blank1_sq_mi =\n<!-- General information  --------------->\n|timezone               =[[West Africa Time|WAT]]\n|utc_offset             = +1\n|timezone_DST           = \n|utc_offset_DST         = \n|coordinates            = \n|elevation_footnotes    =  <!--for references: use <ref> </ref> tags-->\n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_ft           =\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -------->\n|postal_code_type       =  <!-- enter ZIP code, Postcode, Post code, Postal code... -->\n|postal_code            =\n|area_code              =\n|blank_name             =\n|blank_info             =\n|blank1_name            =\n|blank1_info            =\n|website                = \n|footnotes              = \n}}\n\n''' Vina Department ''' is a [[Departments of Cameroon|department]] (''d\u00e9partement'') of the [[Adamawa Province]] in [[Cameroon]].\nThe department covers an area of 17,196&nbsp;km\u00b2 and as of 2001 had a total population of 247,427.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statoids.com/ycm.html|title=Departments of Cameroon|publisher=Statoids, obtained from  Institut national de la statistique (Cameroun) - Annuaire statistique du Cameroun 2004|accessdate=March 10, 2009}}</ref> The capital of the department lies at [[Ngaound\u00e9r\u00e9]].\n\n==Subdivisions==\nThe department is divided administratively into 7 [[Communes of Cameroon|communes]] and in turn into villages.\n\n===Communes===\n# [[Belel, Cameroon|Belel]]\n# [[Mbe, Cameroon|Mbe]]\n# [[Nganha]]\n# [[Ngaound\u00e9r\u00e9]] (urban)\n# [[Ngaound\u00e9r\u00e9]] (rural)\n# [[Nyambaka]]\n# [[Martap]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{coord missing|Cameroon}}\n\n{{Departments of Cameroon}}\n\n[[Category:Departments of Cameroon]]\n[[Category:Adamawa Region]]\n\n\n{{Cameroon-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!--See the Table at Infobox Settlement for all fields and descriptions of usage-->\n<!-- Basic info  ---------------->\n|name          = Vina Department\n|other_name             =\n|native_name            =  <!-- for cities whose native name is not in English -->\n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = [[Departments of Cameroon|Department]]\n|motto                  =\n<!-- images and maps  ----------->\n|image_skyline          =\n|imagesize              = \n|image_caption          = \n|image_flag             = \n|flag_size              =\n|image_seal             = \n|seal_size              =\n|image_shield           = \n|shield_size            =\n|image_map              = CM-Vina.png\n|mapsize                = 300px\n|map_caption            = Department location in Cameroon\n|pushpin_map            = Cameroon#Africa<!-- the name of a location map as per http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Location_map -->\n|pushpin_label_position =bottom\n|pushpin_mapsize        = 300\n|pushpin_map_caption    =\n<!-- Location ------------------>\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = {{flag|Cameroon}}\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Provinces of Cameroon|Province]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Adamawa Province]]\n|subdivision_type2      = Capital\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Ngaound\u00e9r\u00e9]]\n|subdivision_type3      =\n|subdivision_name3      = \n|<!-- Politics ----------------->\n|government_footnotes   =\n|government_type       