and, Simon Goldhill & Edith Hall (''In Our Time'', Feb. 5, 2004)\n{{Achaemenid Empire}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Battle Of Thermopylae}}\n[[Category:Battle of Thermopylae| ]]\n[[Category:480s BC conflicts]]\n[[Category:480 BC]]\n[[Category:Battles involving the Achaemenid Empire]]\n[[Category:Battles of the Greco-Persian Wars|Thermopylae]]\n[[Category:Last stand battles|T]]\n", "name_user": "70.172.137.165", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Thermopylae"}
{"title_page": "Rebel Wilson", "text_new": "{{pp-pc1}}\n{{Short description|Australian actress, comedian, writer and producer}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Rebel Wilson\n| image              = File:Rebel Wilson (6707611099) (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = Wilson in 2012\n| birth_name         = {{nowrap|Melanie Elizabeth Bownds}}\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1980|3|2}}\n| birth_place        = [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]], Australia\n| alma_mater         = [[University of New South Wales]]\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Actress|comedian|writer| producer}}\n| years_active       = 2002\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Rebel Melanie Elizabeth Wilson'''{{efn|According to the [[Australian Electoral Commission|Australian Electoral Roll]], she was born Melanie Elizabeth Bownds.<ref name=\"ASIC2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/lifestyle/celebrity/ls-celebrity-news/rebel-wilsons-birth-date-revealed-in-asic-documents-20150519-gh5caq.html|title=Rebel Wilson's birth date revealed in ASIC documents|last1=Aubusson|first1=Kate|date=20 May 2015|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|accessdate=19 May 2015|quote=Business records filed with the Australian Securities and Investment Commission (ASIC) list the date of birth for a \"Rebel Melanie Elizabeth Wilson\" as March 2, 1980}}</ref><ref name=\"Miller\">{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/ipad/the-qa-with-actor-rebel-wilson/story-fn6bn9st-1226199246884|title=The Q&A with actor Rebel Wilson|last=Miller|first=Megan|date=19 November 2011|work=[[Herald Sun]]|accessdate=13 August 2013|publisher=[[The Herald and Weekly Times]]}}</ref> In later years she adopted \"Rebel\"\u2013a childhood [[nickname]]\u2013as her first name and changed her [[surname]] to Wilson. She retained her first two given names as [[middle name]]s.<ref name=\"ASIC2\"/><ref name=\"People 20 May 2015\">{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/article/rebel-wilson-age-name-melanie-elizabeth-bownds|title=Facts vs. Fibs: Rebel Wilson's Real Age is 35, Records Confirm|last=Fowler|first=Tara|date=20 May 2015|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|publisher=Time|accessdate=21 May 2015|quote=The Australian Electoral Roll lists her real name as Melanie Elizabeth Bownds, though she later changed her last name to Wilson, as has been previously reported. Last year, however, she told The Australian Women's Weekly that her real name was in fact Rebel, and that Melanie and Elizabeth were middle names she went by at school to avoid being teased.}}</ref>|group=note}} (born '''Melanie Elizabeth Bownds'''; 2 March 1980) is an Australian actress, writer, comedian and producer. After graduating from the [[Australian Theatre for Young People]] in 2003, she began appearing as Toula on the [[Special Broadcasting Service]] (SBS) comedy series ''[[Pizza (TV series)|Pizza]]'' and the [[sketch comedy]] series ''[[The Wedge (Australian TV series)|The Wedge]]''. In 2008, Wilson wrote, produced and starred in the musical comedy series ''[[Bogan Pride]]''. The following year, she won the [[Tropfest]] best actress award for her role in ''Bargain'' and made a guest appearance in ''[[City Homicide]]''. Shortly after moving to the United States, Wilson was cast as Brynn in the feature film ''[[Bridesmaids (2011 film)|Bridesmaids]]''.\n\nWilson also appeared in ''[[A Few Best Men]]'', ''[[What to Expect When You're Expecting (film)|What to Expect When You're Expecting]]'' and ''[[Struck by Lightning (2012 film)|Struck by Lightning]]'', leading ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' to name her one of their \"Top Ten Comics to Watch for 2011.\" She also appeared as Becky in ''[[Bachelorette (film)|Bachelorette]]'' and starred in the musical comedy ''[[Pitch Perfect (film series)|Pitch Perfect]]'' [[film series]] as Fat Amy, a role that earned her several award nominations and wins, including the MTV Best Breakthrough Performance Award and a Teen Choice Award for Choice Movie Actress. She has also created and starred in ''[[Super Fun Night]]'', a television comedy that aired for one season on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]. In 2019, Wilson starred in ''[[Isn't It Romantic (2019 film)|Isn't It Romantic]]'', her first lead role. She went on to play a con artist in ''[[The Hustle (film)|The Hustle]]'', a female-centred remake of ''[[Dirty Rotten Scoundrels (film)|Dirty Rotten Scoundrels]]'', and [[Jennyanydots]] in ''[[Cats (2019 film)|Cats]]''.\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nWilson was born on 2 March 1980<ref name=\"ASIC2\"/> in [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]], Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biography.com/people/rebel-wilson-21187753|title=Rebel Wilson |website = Biography.com }}</ref> Her mother, Sue, is a [[professional handler|professional dog handler]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Ch Nangunyah Billy Elliot|url= https://www.dogzonline.com.au/breeds/profile.asp?dog=38487|website=dogzonline.com.au|accessdate=21 May 2015}}</ref><ref name=EllenShow>{{cite episode|title=Rebel Wilson on Her Family|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=astcvS4QCfQ|series=[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]]|network=[[NBCUniversal]]|quote=I've got two sisters, Liberty and Annachi and my brother Ryot...and what's her [mother's] name? Sue.|airdate = 11 November 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"MField\" /> Wilson grew up in the suburbs of [[Kenthurst, New South Wales|Kenthurst]], [[Parramatta]] and [[Castle Hill, New South Wales|Castle Hill]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/tv--radio/bboganvilleb-dont-mock-the-moccasins/2008/06/16/1213468329184.html|title=Don't be mocking the moccasins.|date=17 June 2008|work=[[The Age]]|accessdate=24 December 2013}}</ref> She attended [[Tara Anglican School for Girls]].<ref name=\"Miller\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elle.com.au/culture/elle-interview-rebel-wilson-7664 |title=Elle interview: Rebel Wilson|date=17 December 2013|work=[[Elle (magazine)|Elle Australia]]|accessdate=24 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://movieline.com/2012/09/07/bridesmaids-bachelorette-rebel-wilson-pitch-perfect-interview |title=From Bridesmaids To Bachelorette: Why Rebel Wilson Is The Most Interesting Woman In Hollywood|publisher=[[Movieline]] |date=7 September 2012|first=Jen|last=Yamato|accessdate=21 August 2014}}</ref> She completed her [[Higher School Certificate (New South Wales)|Higher School Certificate]] in 1997, including second place in the state in Food Technology.<ref>{{cite web |title=Food Technology 2 unit|url=http://www.boardofstudies.nsw.edu.au/ebos/static/OM_CM_1997_12_21870.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190809202449/https://www.boardofstudies.nsw.edu.au/ebos/static/OM_CM_1997_12_21870.htm|archivedate=9 August 2019|url-status=live|website=[[Board of Studies]]|accessdate=19 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nWilson has three siblings: sisters Liberty and Annaleise (who uses the name \"Annarchi\") and a brother, who uses the name \"Ryot.\"<ref name=EllenShow /><ref name=\"MField\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/lifestyle/sunday-magazine/winning-laughs-and-losing-weight/story-e6frf039-1226186071421|title=Winning Laughs and Losing Weight|last=Field|first= Melissa|date=6 November 2011|work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]]|publisher=News Limited|accessdate=1 January 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Craig\">{{cite episode|series=[[The Late Late Show with Craig Ferguson]]|network=[[CBS]]|last=Ferguson|first=Craig (Host)|title=Carla Gugino, Rebel Wilson|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=heoG04WIPQg|season=7|number=176|date=3 June 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2017/jun/01/rebel-wilsons-siblings-argue-family-has-tradition-of-unusual-names-at-trial|title=Rebel Wilson's siblings argue family has tradition of 'unusual' names at trial|author=Australian Associated Press|date=1 June 2017|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=8 June 2018}}</ref> Liberty and Ryot appeared on the [[The Amazing Race Australia 1|first season]] of ''[[The Amazing Race Australia]]'' in 2011, where they were the first team eliminated.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/ipad/rebel-sets-pace-for-siblings/story-fn6ck8la-1226056983991|title=Rebel sets pace for siblings|last=Shearer|first=Geoff|date=17 May 2011|work=[[The Courier-Mail]]|publisher=[[Queensland Newspapers]]|accessdate=15 August 2011}}</ref> Wilson has stated that her great-aunt was [[Lillian Bounds]], who was married to [[Walt Disney]] until his death in 1966.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/weekend/entertainment/2013/10/11/funny-girl-rebel-wilson/2965553|title=Funny girl Rebel Wilson's 'Super Fun Night' inspiration|work=[[USA Today]]|date=11 October 2013|first=Nancy|last=Mills|accessdate=21 August 2014}}</ref> Despite Wilson standing by this belief in court,<ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/06/15/rebel-wilson-wins-age-defamation-lawsuit-rapping-court/|title=Rebel Wilson wins defamation case after rapping, joking and crying during bizarre court performance|last =Pearlman|first=Jonathan|date=15 June 2017|work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|accessdate=17 June 2017}}</ref> it continues to be disputed by genealogist Dale Sheldon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nz.news.yahoo.com/rebel-wilson-isnt-disney-genealogist-173100034--spt.html|title=Rebel Wilson isn't a Disney: genealogist|website=[[Yahoo!]]|accessdate=8 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nWilson's first career choice was mathematics. She told ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]'', \"I was very academic at high school and was always good with numbers.\"<ref name=\"PushOver\">{{cite news|url=http://newsstore.fairfax.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?page=1&sy=age&kw=Rebel+Wilson+and+University&pb=all_ffx&dt=selectRange&dr=entire&so=relevance&sf=text&sf=headline&rc=10&rm=200&sp=nrm&clsPage=1&docID=SMH020529M6EBJ21STPN|title=A push over on stage|last=Wilson |first=Vanessa|date=29 May 2002|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|accessdate=15 August 2011|quote =That lead to the 22-year-old's first play, The Westie Monologues, and her springboard to life as a playwright. And actor. And producer. And theatre company director.}}{{Dead link|date=August 2019}}</ref> She attended the [[University of New South Wales]], graduating in 2009 with [[Bachelor of Arts]] (Theatre and Performance Studies) and [[Bachelor of Laws]] degrees.<ref>{{cite web|title=Leaders|url=https://www.arts.unsw.edu.au/alumni-supporters/alumni/leaders|publisher=[[University of New South Wales]]|accessdate=20 May 2015}}</ref> A former [[Rotary International]] [[youth ambassador]] for Australia, she was based in South Africa for one year, where she contracted [[malaria]].<ref name=\"PushOver\" /><ref name=\"TopTen\">{{cite web|url =http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118040424?refCatId=19|title=10 Comics to Watch \u2013 Rebel Wilson: Oz Star Gets ''Bridesmaids'' Boost|last=Blair|first=Iain|date=26 July 2011|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Reed Business Information]] |accessdate=15 August 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108233134/http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118040424?refCatId=19|archivedate=8 November 2012}}</ref> She has spoken of malaria-induced hallucinations, where she saw herself as an actress who had won an [[Academy Award|Oscar]], convincing her to pursue an acting career.<ref name=\"TopTen\" />\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early career (2002\u20132010)===\n\nWilson studied at the [[Australian Theatre for Young People]] (ATYP).<ref name=\"MeetTheCast\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sbs.com.au/shows/boganpride/cast/detail/id/8|title=Meet the cast \u2013 Rebel Wilson|publisher=[[Special Broadcasting Service]]|accessdate=15 August 2011}}</ref> In 2003 she moved to New York after winning the ATYP International scholarship, which was funded by [[Nicole Kidman]]. While she was in New York, Wilson trained with [[The Second City]].<ref name=\"off to New York\">{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2002/09/24/1032734164283.html|title=Rebel off to New York to hone comic craft|last=Pryor|first=Lisa|date=25 September 2002|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|accessdate=15 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/news/rebel-wilson-credits-nicole-kidman-with-movie-career_1229895|title=Rebel Wilson Credits Nicole Kidman With Movie Career|date=30 June 2011|publisher=[[Contactmusic.com]]|accessdate=15 April 2013}}</ref> She appeared with the [[Sydney Theatre Company]] and performed at the [[Melbourne International Comedy Festival]].<ref name=\"MeetTheCast\" /> She first came to the public's attention in 2002 with her stage musical ''The Westie Monologues'', which she wrote,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bownds|first1=Melanie Elizabeth|title=The Westie Monologues|url=http://www.ipaustralia.com.au/applicant/bownds-melanie-elizabeth/trademarks/878718| publisher=ipaustralia.com.au|accessdate=19 May 2015}}</ref> starred in and produced in Sydney.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://newsstore.fairfax.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?page=1&sy=age&kw=Rebel+Wilson+and+University&pb=all_ffx&dt=selectRange&dr=entire&so=relevance&sf=text&sf=headline&rc=10&rm=200&sp=nrm&clsPage=1&docID=SMH021125D24F90EPAMU|title=Rebel with a cause to liberate westies by poking fun|last=Verity|first=William|date = 25 November 2002 |work = [[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |publisher = [[Fairfax Media]] |accessdate = 15 August 2011 }}</ref> Her follow-up stage productions, which she wrote, produced and starred in include ''Spunks'' and ''Confessions of an Exchange Student''.<ref name=\"PushOver\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://newsstore.fairfax.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?page=1&sy=age&kw=Rebel+Wilson+and+Confessions+of+an+Exchange+Student&pb=all_ffx&dt=selectRange&dr=entire&so=relevance&sf=text&sf=headline&rc=10&rm=200&sp=nrm&clsPage=1&docID=AGE0504097N2885VQGS6|title = Comedy|last=Bragge |first=Lily|date=9 April 2005|work=[[The Age]]|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|accessdate=15 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn Australia, Wilson is most known for her roles as Toula on the [[SBS (Australian TV channel)|SBS]] comedy series ''[[Pizza (TV series)|Pizza]]'' and as various characters including Lucy, Fat Mandi and Karla Bangs on the sketch comedy series ''[[The Wedge (Australian TV series)|The Wedge]]''.<ref name=\"TopTen\" /> She played an ''[[Australian Idol]]'' mad schoolgirl in a series of [[Telstra]] advertisements shown during ''Australian Idol'' from 2004 to 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2008/10/bogan-pride.html|title=Bogan Pride|last=Knox|first=David|date=2 October 2008 |publisher=[[TV Tonight]]|accessdate=15 August 2011}}</ref> She also had roles in the feature films ''[[Fat Pizza]]'' and ''[[Ghost Rider (2007 film)|Ghost Rider]]''.<ref name=\"Pride\">{{cite news|url=http://www.watoday.com.au/articles/2008/09/23/1221935644974.html|title=Pride of place in bogan-ville|last=McManus|first=Bridget|date=25 September 2008|work=[[WAtoday]] |publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|accessdate=16 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Wilson created, wrote, produced and starred in the musical comedy series ''[[Bogan Pride]]'' on SBS One and also starred in the improvisational [[Nine Network]] series ''[[Monster House (Australian TV series)|Monster House]]''.<ref name=\"TopTen\" /><ref name=\"Pride\" /> In 2009 Wilson won the [[Tropfest]] Best Actress award for her role in the film ''Bargain''.<ref name=\"AboutTown\">{{cite news|url=http://newsstore.fairfax.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?page=1&sy=age&kw=Rebel+Wilson+and+Tropfest&pb=all_ffx&dt=selectRange&dr=entire&so=relevance&sf=text&sf=headline&rc=10&rm=200&sp=nrm&clsPage=1&docID=SAG090301174AT1CC2OK|title=About Town|last=Kent|first=Melissa|date=1 March 2009|work=[[The Age]]|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|accessdate=15 August 2011}}</ref> She has made appearances on the improvisational comedy show ''[[Thank God You're Here]]'' and the comedy game show ''[[Talkin' 'Bout Your Generation]]''.<ref name=\"MeetTheCast\" /><ref>{{cite news|url =http://newsstore.fairfax.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?page=1&sy=age&kw=Rebel+Wilson+and+Generation&pb=all_ffx&dt=selectRange&dr=entire&so=relevance&sf=text&sf=headline&rc=10&rm=200&sp=nrm&clsPage=1&docID=NCH0905196I6TV6EM3QS |title=Highlights |last=Beaumont|first=Anita|date=19 May 2009|work=[[Newcastle Herald]]|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|accessdate=15 August 2011}}</ref> She performed stand-up on the television special ''The Breast Darn Show In Town'' and guest starred in the [[Seven Network]] drama ''[[City Homicide]]'' and performed improv at the [[Upright Citizens Brigade]] in Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite episode|url=http://www.throng.com.au/city-homicide/city-homicide-dead-weight-s03e19|series=City Homicide|title=Dead Weight|season=3|number=19|date=4 November 2009|publisher=Throng|network=[[Seven Network|Seven]]|accessdate=15 August 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Move to Hollywood (2011\u2013present)===\n\nAfter moving to the United States, Wilson signed to talent and literary agents [[William Morris Endeavor]].<ref name=\"OurRebel\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/sydney-confidential/our-rebel-wilson-is-matt-lucas-secret-sister-in-next-movie-bridesmaids/story-e6frewz0-1225870281103|title=Our Rebel Wilson is Matt Lucas' secret sister in next movie Bridesmaids|date=24 May 2010|work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]]|publisher=[[News Limited]]|accessdate=15 August 2011}}</ref> Wilson's next film role came in the [[Judd Apatow]] film, ''[[Bridesmaids (2011 film)|Bridesmaids]]'', in which she played Brynn, the sister of [[Matt Lucas]]' character.<ref name=\"OurRebel\" /> The role was written especially for her.<ref name=\"Rafanelli\" /> Wilson then appeared in the CBS sitcom ''[[Rules of Engagement (TV series)|Rules of Engagement]]'' and on the [[Comedy Central]] series, ''[[Workaholics]]''.<ref name=\"Joan\">{{cite web|url= http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2010/10/when-rebel-met-joan.html|title=When Rebel met Joan|last=Knox|first=David|date=21 October 2010|publisher=[[TV Tonight]]|accessdate=15 August 2011}}</ref> She co-hosted the 2010 [[ARIA Music Awards]] and performed at the inaugural ''Variety''\u2019s Power of Comedy event in Los Angeles with Lucas and [[Russell Brand]].<ref name=\"Joan\" /> In early 2011, Wilson filmed ''[[A Few Best Men]]'' at Fox Studios Australia.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/aussie-rebel-without-a-pause-in-america/story-e6frf96x-1226063714396|title=Aussie Rebel without a pause in America|date=26 May 2011|work=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]]|publisher=[[News Limited]]|accessdate=15 August 2011}}</ref> She also filmed a role in ''[[Small Apartments]]''.<ref name=\"Expecting\">{{cite web|url=http://insidemovies.ew.com/2011/07/11/rebel-wilson-what-to-expect-when-youre-expecting|title='Bridesmaids' scene-stealer Rebel Wilson joins 'What To Expect When You're Expecting'|last=Murphy|first=Shaunna|date=11 July 2011|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Warner]]|accessdate=11 August 2011}}</ref> Wilson was named one of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' magazine's \"Top Ten Comics to Watch for 2011.\"<ref name=\"TopTen\" /> In 2012, Wilson had a role in the ensemble comedy ''[[What to Expect When You're Expecting (film)|What to Expect When You're Expecting]]'', as Janice,<ref name=\"Expecting\" /> and co-starred in the indie film ''[[Struck by Lightning (2012 film)|Struck By Lightning]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118040403 |title=Wilson rides Colfer's 'Lightning'|last=McNary|first=Dave|date=25 July 2011|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Reed Business Information]]|accessdate=11 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 August 2011, Borys Kit of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' reported that Wilson had replaced [[Casey Wilson]] in ''[[Bachelorette (film)|Bachelorette]]''.<ref name=\"Ramps\">{{cite news |url = http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/bridesmaids-star-ramps-up-movie-225490 |title='Bridesmaids' Co-Star Ramps Up Movie Roles (Exclusive)|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=19 August 2011|last=Borys|first=Kit|accessdate=20 August 2011}}</ref> In 2012, Wilson voiced a character in ''[[Ice Age: Continental Drift]]''<ref name=\"Ramps\" /> and played Fat Amy in ''[[Pitch Perfect]]''. For the latter role, she received critical acclaim and earned various award nominations, including Best Supporting Actress from the [[San Diego Film Critics Society]] and [[18th Critics' Choice Awards#Best Actress in a Comedy|Best Actress in a Comedy]] from the [[Broadcast Film Critics Association]].<ref name=\"SanDiego\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sdfcs.org/san-diego-film-critics-nominate-top-films-for-2012|title=San Diego Film Critics Nominate Top Films for 2012|date=9 December 2012|publisher=[[San Diego Film Critics Society]]|accessdate=10 December 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"CriticsChoice\">{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/race/critics-choice-movie-awards-lincoln-400446|first=Kimberly|last=Nordyke|title='Lincoln' Leads Critics' Choice Movie Awards Nominees With Record-Setting 13 Mentions|date=11 December 2012|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=9 August 2019}}</ref> She won the [[MTV Movie Award for Best Actor in a Movie]] and shared the Best Musical Moment award with her ''Pitch Perfect'' co-stars. Wilson was also nominated for [[MTV Movie Award for Best Performance]].<ref name=\"Goodacre\">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/movies/news/a466341/mtv-movie-awards-2013-the-winners-in-full.html|title=MTV Movie Awards 2013 \u2013 The winners in full|date=15 April 2013|last=Goodacre|first=Kate|work=[[Digital Spy]]|publisher=[[Hearst Magazines UK]]|accessdate=15 April 2013}}</ref> Wilson later won the Choice Movie Actress: Comedy award for ''Pitch Perfect'' at the [[2013 Teen Choice Awards]].<ref name=\"WSJ\">{{cite news|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2013/08/11/teen-choice-awards-2013-live-blog|title=Teen Choice Awards 2013: Live Blog|date=11 August 2013|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|publisher=[[News Corp (2013\u2013present)|News Corp]]|accessdate=12 August 2013}}</ref> She had also been nominated for Choice Comedian at the 2013 Teen Choice Awards.<ref name=\"Wightman\">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/ustv/news/a483821/teen-choice-awards-2013-first-wave-nominees-in-full.html|title=Teen Choice Awards 2013: First wave nominees in full|last=Wightman|first=Catriona|date=22 May 2013|work=[[Digital Spy]]|publisher=[[Hearst Magazines UK]]|accessdate=22 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Rebel Wilson 2019 3.png|thumb|right|180px|Wilson in 2019.]]\nIn January 2012, [[Michael Ausiello]] of [[TVLine]] announced that Wilson would be writing and starring in ''[[Super Fun Night]]'', a comedy that follows three friends on a quest to have fun every Friday night.<ref name=\"Ausiello\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tvline.com/2012/01/cbs-pilot-super-fun-night-rebel-wilson|title=Pilot Scoop: CBS Greenlights Super Fun Comedy Starring Bridesmaids Breakout Rebel Wilson|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|authorlink=Michael Ausiello|date=26 January 2012 |publisher=[[TVLine]]|accessdate=28 January 2012}}</ref> The pilot was picked up by [[CBS]] and [[Conan O'Brien]] became one of the executive producers.<ref name=\"Ausiello\" /> The pilot was later turned down by CBS, but the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] network picked up the project.<ref name=\"Andreeva\">{{cite web|url=http://www.deadline.com/2012/06/rebel-wilsons-cbs-comedy-pilot-super-fun-night-close-to-new-pilot-order-at-abc|title=Rebel Wilson's CBS Comedy Pilot 'Super Fun Night' Close To New Order At ABC|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=5 June 2012|publisher=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=6 June 2012}}</ref> A series was ordered and the show began broadcasting on 2 October 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.eonline.com/news/417693/abc-scoop-rebel-wilson-s-super-fun-night-bridesmaids-star-s-conan-o-brien-produced-comedy-ordered-to-series|title =News/ABC Scoop: Rebel Wilson's Super Fun Night, Bridesmaids Star's Conan O'Brien-Produced Comedy Ordered to Series|last=Bricker|first=Tierney|date=10 May 2013|work=[[E!#E! Online|E! Online]]|publisher=[[NBCUniversal]]|accessdate=2 October 2013}}</ref> The series was cancelled after one season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/05/09/suburgatory-canceled-by-abc/262441|title='Suburgatory', 'Super Fun Night' Canceled by ABC|last=Kondolojy|first=Amanda |publisher=[[TV by the Numbers]]|accessdate=9 May 2014}}</ref> Wilson played Robin Peck in [[Michael Bay]]'s ''[[Pain & Gain]]'' (2013).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://insidemovies.ew.com/2012/03/27/rebel-wilson-pain-and-gain|title=Rebel Wilson to Join Michael Bay's True Crime Drama 'Pain and Gain'|last=Vary|first=Adam B.|date=27 March 2012|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |publisher=[[Time Warner]]|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.painandgainmovie.com/#|title=Cast \u2013 Rebel Wilson|publisher=[[Paramount Pictures]]|accessdate=28 April 2013}}</ref> She hosted the [[2013 MTV Movie Awards]] on 14 April 2013.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2251479/Rebel-Wilson-gets-whipped-shape-Matt-Lucas-new-trailer-shes-named-host-MTV-Movie-Awards.html|title=Rebel Wilson named as host of MTV Movie Awards|date=21 December 2012|work=[[Daily Mail]]|publisher=[[Associated Newspapers]]|accessdate=21 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2014, the American [[satellite television]] network [[Dish Network]] launched a marketing campaign for its [[Dish Hopper (DVR)|Hopper]] [[Digital video recorder|DVR]] featuring Wilson as the voice of the eponymous [[Computer animation|computer animated]] [[kangaroo]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://about.dish.com/press-release/corporate/dish-launches-new-marketing-campaign-featuring-voice-award-winning-actress-r|title=DISH Launches New Marketing Campaign Featuring Voice of Award-Winning Actress Rebel Wilson as Hopper the Kangaroo|date=17 March 2014|work=[[DISH Network]]|accessdate=19 June 2014}}</ref> Wilson reprised her role in the sequels ''[[Pitch Perfect 2]]'' (2015) and ''[[Pitch Perfect 3]]'' (2017).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/06/15/anna-kendrick-rebel-wilson-pitch-perfect-3_n_7589552.html|title=Anna Kendrick And Rebel Wilson To Return For 'Pitch Perfect 3'|work=[[HuffPost]]|date=15 June 2015}}</ref> She also made a cameo in the television comedy ''[[Pompidou (TV series)|Pompidou]]''.<ref name=\"Rafanelli\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/may/02/rebel-wilson-pitch-perfect-2-bridesmaids-comedy-boys-club|title=Rebel Wilson: 'Comedy has been a boys' club \u2013 until now'|last=Rafanelli|first=Stephanie|date=11 May 2015|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=15 June 2017}}</ref> Wilson joined the voice cast for ''[[Kung Fu Panda&nbsp;3]]'';<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/kung-fu-panda-3-release-788851|title='Kung Fu Panda 3' Release Date Moves Up Two Months|last=Ford|first=Rebecca|date=14 April 2015|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=26 January 2016}}</ref> however, in September 2015, she was replaced with [[Kate Hudson]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kit|first1=Borys|title=Kate Hudson to Replace Rebel Wilson in 'Kung Fu Panda 3' (Exclusive)|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/kate-hudson-replace-rebel-wilson-820343|accessdate=4 September 2015|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=4 September 2015}}</ref> Wilson next appeared in the ensemble comedy ''[[How to Be Single]]'', released in February 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/dakota-johnson-rebel-wilson-dan-768417|title=Dakota Johnson, Rebel Wilson, Dan Stevens Joining 'How to Be Single' (Exclusive)|last=Ford|first=Rebecca| last2=Kit|first2=Borys|date=29 January 2015|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=20 March 2015}}</ref> Nigel M. Smith of ''[[The Guardian]]'' wrote, \"Wilson is the standout, nailing every pratfall she's dealt, but ''How to Be Single'' doesn't make strong use of her character.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/feb/12/how-to-be-single-review-rebel-wilson-dakota-johnson|title=How To Be Single review \u2013 Rebel Wilson underused in diverting singleton comedy| last=Smith|first=Nigel M.|date=12 February 2016|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=13 February 2016}}</ref> Wilson also appeared in the action comedy ''[[Grimsby (film)|Grimsby]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/rebel-wilson-grimsby-sacha-baron-cohen-1201219186|title=Rebel Wilson Joins Sacha Baron Cohen in Sony's 'Grimsby' (Exclusive)|last=Kroll|first=Justin|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=19 June 2014}}</ref> On 14 February 2016, Wilson presented the nominations for the [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Supporting Role|Best Supporting Actor]] category at the [[69th British Academy Film Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Horton|first=Helena|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/baftas/12157086/Rebel-Wilson-calls-Oscars-racist-in-hilarious-Bafta-speech.html|title=Video: Rebel Wilson calls Oscars 'racist' in hilarious Bafta speech|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=15 February 2016|accessdate=18 March 2016}}</ref> Wilson is one of sixty celebrities who make a cameo in ''[[Absolutely Fabulous: The Movie]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/article/rebel-wilson-officially-making-cameo-ab-fab-movie-|title=Rebel Wilson Shares Pics of Her ''Absolutely Fabulous'' Time on the Set of Upcoming Movie|first=Michael|last=Miller|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=2 December 2015|accessdate=16 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nWilson appeared as [[Ursula (Disney)|Ursula]], the sea witch, in an all-star concert version of ''[[The Little Mermaid (musical)|The Little Mermaid]]'' at the [[Hollywood Bowl]] on 3 June 4 June, and 6 June 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-cm-little-mermaid-hollywood-bowl-20160601-snapsara-20160601-snap-story.html|title=In a post-'Brave,' post-'Frozen' world, why the time is right for Hollywood Bowl's 'Little Mermaid'|last=Martens|first=Todd|date=1 June 2016|publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=1 June 2016}}</ref> She made her [[West End Theatre|West End]] debut in the musical ''[[Guys and Dolls]]'' in the role of Miss Adelaide from 28 June to 21 August 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whatsonstage.com/london-theatre/news/rebel-wilson-guys-and-dolls-west-end_40656.html|title=Rebel Wilson to make West End debut in Guys and Dolls|publisher=WhatsOnStage|accessdate=5 August 2016}}</ref> She received positive reviews.<ref name=\"DRS\" /> Wilson played LeFou in a production of ''Beauty and the Beast: Live in Concert'' at the Hollywood Bowl on 25\u201326 May 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/movies/news/a858132/rebel-wilson-beauty-and-the-beast-hollywood-bowl-concert-lefou/|title=Rebel Wilson transforms into LeFou for Beauty and the Beast: Live in Concert|last=Houghton|first=Rianne|date=27 May 2018|work=[[Digital Spy]]|accessdate=15 June 2018}}</ref> She also appeared on the cover of ''[[Vogue Australia]]'' for the first time.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/life/entertainthis/2018/05/23/rebel-wilson-covers-vogue-australia-shuts-down-photoshopping-claims/636113002/|title=Rebel Wilson covers 'Vogue Australia,' shuts down Photoshopping accusations on Twitter|last=Moniuszko|first=Sara M.|date=23 May 2018|work=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=15 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nWilson has thus far starred in two 2019 comedies. The first, ''[[Isn't It Romantic (2019 film)|Isn't It Romantic]]'', was released in February, and is about a woman (Wilson) who wakes up in a literal [[romantic comedy]], despite the character's hate for the genre; the film is Wilson's first solo lead role.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/06/betty-gilpin-isnt-it-romantic-movie-casting-rebel-wilson-1202113390/|title=Betty Gilpin Joins Rebel Wilson In 'Isn't It Romantic' Movie At New Line|last=Hipes|first=Patrick|date=14 June 2017|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=15 June 2017}}</ref> In May, Wilson starred alongside [[Anne Hathaway]] in ''[[The Hustle (film)|The Hustle]]'', a female-centred remake of the 1988 comedy film ''[[Dirty Rotten Scoundrels (film)|Dirty Rotten Scoundrels]]''. Wilson also co-produced the latter film.<ref name=\"DRS\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-36991037|title=Rebel Wilson set for Dirty Rotten Scoundrels remake|date=5 August 2016|publisher=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=5 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/anne-hathaway-joining-rebel-wilson-dirty-rotten-scoundrels-remake-952110 |title=Anne Hathaway Joining Rebel Wilson in 'Dirty Rotten Scoundrels' Remake| last=Ford|first=Rebecca|last2=Kit| first2=Borys|date=19 January 2017|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=15 June 2017}}</ref> Wilson plays twins Doreen and Dolores Bognor in Australian drama series ''[[Les Norton (TV series)|Les Norton]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.if.com.au/abc-sets-premiere-for-roadshow-rough-diamond-drama-les-norton/|title=ABC sets premiere for Roadshow Rough Diamond drama ''Les Norton''|last=Groves|first=Dan|date=4 July 2019|work=[[If Magazine]]|accessdate=5 November 2019}}</ref> Towards the end of 2019, Wilson played Fraulein Rahm in [[Taika Waititi]]'s dark comedy drama ''[[Jojo Rabbit]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=http://deadline.com/2018/05/rebel-wilson-jojo-rabbit-taika-waititi-wwii-satire-frightening-fraulein-fox-searchlight-1202395823/|title=Rebel Wilson Joins Taika Waititi's WWII Satire 'Jojo Rabbit' As Frightful Fraulein|last=Fleming Jr.|first=Mike|date=22 May 2018|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=15 June 2018}}</ref> and [[Jennyanydots]] in the musical film ''[[Cats (2019 film)|Cats]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2018/11/cats-movie-rebel-wilson-cast-as-jennyanydots-andrew-lloyd-webber-1202504908/|title=Rebel Wilson To Play Jennyanydots In Universal-Working Title's 'Cats'|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|date=19 November 2018|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]| accessdate=19 November 2018}}</ref> Wilson hosts the dog styling competition ''[[Pooch Perfect]]'' for [[Seven Network]]. The show features professional dog stylists competing over a number of challenges for a $100,000 prize.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2019/09/rebel-wilson-to-host-pooch-perfect-for-seven.html|title=Rebel Wilson to host Pooch Perfect for Seven|last=Knox|first=David|date=3 September 2019|publisher=[[TV Tonight]]|accessdate=5 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Upcoming films===\nWilson will appear in a remake of ''[[Private Benjamin (1980 film)|Private Benjamin]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/article/rebel-wilson-private-benjamin-remake-goldie-hawn-pitch-perfect|title=Rebel Wilson to Star in ''Private Benjamin'' Remake|last=Billups|first=Andrea|date=9 May 2014|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate=9 May 2014}}</ref> She has also been cast in ''The Social Life'' alongside [[Amanda Seyfried]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://deadline.com/2014/04/sony-buys-lauryn-kahn-spec-im-in-love-with-the-dj-for-gary-sanchez-716141|title=Sony Buys Lauryn Kahn Spec 'I'm In Love With The DJ' For Gary Sanchez|last=Fleming, Jr.|first= Mike|date=17 April 2014|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=20 March 2015}}</ref> Wilson will produce and star in a feature film adaptation of the [[Image Comics]] comic book ''Crowded''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chitwood|first1=Adam|title=Rebel Wilson to Produce and Star in Comic Adaptation 'Crowded'|url=http://collider.com/rebel-wilson-crowded-movie/|publisher=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|accessdate=26 June 2018|date=26 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Media controversy==\n\nIn May 2015, Australian magazine ''[[Woman's Day (Australian magazine)|Woman's Day]]'' published a story claiming that Wilson had been misleading about her birth name, age, and upbringing.<ref name=\"WomensDay\">{{cite web|url=http://www.womansday.com.au/celebrity/australian-celebrities/will-the-real-rebel-wilson-please-stand-up-12574|title=Separating fact from fiction: Will the real Rebel Wilson please stand up?|work=[[Woman's Day]]|date=18 May 2015|accessdate=11 July 2015| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150521080051/http://www.womansday.com.au/celebrity/australian-celebrities/will-the-real-rebel-wilson-please-stand-up-12574|archivedate=21 May 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Wilson had previously said in interviews that she was raised by dog-training \"[[bogan]]\" parents in the [[ghetto]] of Sydney, spent a year in Zimbabwe, climbed into a cage with a leopard, got caught in a shoot-out and then struck down by a severe strain of [[malaria]] from a [[mosquito]] in Mozambique where, from her [[Intensive care unit|intensive care]] bed, she envisioned herself winning an [[Academy Awards|Oscar]] and rapping her acceptance speech.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://gulfnews.com/life-style/celebrity/hollywood/rebel-wilson-the-beautiful-bogan-1.1509874|title=Rebel Wilson: the beautiful bogan|work=Guardian News|date=13 May 2015|via=[[Gulf News]]}}</ref> Her age was also incorrectly given as 29 (when it was actually 35), which she would later admit was something she chose not to correct.<ref name=\"Telegraph\" /> ''Woman's Day'' called all of this into question and claimed that Wilson had, on the contrary, a \"very normal, upper-middle-class upbringing\" and \"added a touch of 'fantasy' to the life she led before becoming a household name.\"<ref name=\"WomensDay\" /> The story was picked up by several other publications including ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]'', ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/article/rebel-wilson-age-name-melanie-elizabeth-bownds|title=Facts vs. Fibs: Rebel Wilson's Real Age Is 35, Records Confirm|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=20 May 2015|first=Tara|last=Fowler|accessdate=11 July 2015}}</ref> the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''<ref>{{cite news|url = http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/ct-rebel-wilson-age-20150524-story.html|title=Why would Rebel Wilson lie about her age?|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=24 May 2015|first=Justin Wm.|last=Moyer|accessdate=11 July 2015}}</ref> and ''[[HuffPost|The Huffington Post]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/05/19/rebel-wilson-name-age_n_7320604.html|title=Rebel Wilson Responds To Claims She's Lying About Her Name And Age|work=[[HuffPost]]|date=19 May 2015|first=Stephanie|last=Marcus|accessdate=11 July 2015}}</ref> Most notably, Wilson's true birth date was confirmed through business records filed with the [[Australian Securities and Investment Commission|ASIC]], which were obtained by ''The Sydney Morning Herald''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/lifestyle/celebrity/ls-celebrity-news/rebel-wilsons-birth-date-revealed-in-asic-documents-20150520-gh5caq|title=Rebel Wilson's Birth Date Revealed in ASIC Documents|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=20 May 2015 |accessdate=11 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 May 2016, Wilson said print and online articles in ''Woman's Day'', the Australian ''Women's Weekly'', ''[[NW (magazine)|NW]]'' and ''OK!'' magazines made her out to be a serial liar. According to a [[defamation]] writ filed in the [[Supreme Court of Victoria]], Wilson said her reputation and credit had suffered and she had been humiliated and embarrassed. She also sued for special damages, claiming she missed out on roles and other ones were terminated because of the articles.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/rebel-wilson-sues-magazine-publisher-over-stories-about-her-age-20160516-gowi9a.html|title=Rebel Wilson sues magazine publisher Bauer Media over stories about her age|last=Ham|first=Larissa|date=16 May 2016|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|accessdate=16 May 2016}}</ref> Wilson was represented by [[Matthew Collins (barrister)|Matthew Collins QC]]. On 15 June 2017, a six-person jury ruled in Wilson's favour, finding that publisher [[Bauer Media Group]] had indeed wrongly painted the actress as a serial liar, and that publishing the articles was likely to have caused harm to her career.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/jun/15/rebel-wilson-wins-defamation-trial-against-bauer-media|title=Rebel Wilson wins defamation trial against Bauer Media|date=15 June 2017|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=17 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 September 2017, Wilson was awarded {{A$|4500000|link=yes}} in damages. Wilson's lawyer Richard Leder, said \"Today's verdict is a significant record\u2014it's about four times the highest previous verdict in a defamation case in Australia.\" In June 2017, Wilson tweeted \"Any dollars I receive will go to charity, scholarships or invested into the Aussie film industry to provide jobs.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-09-13/rebel-wilson-defamation-damages/8936850|title=Rebel Wilson awarded $4.5m in damages over defamatory magazine articles|date=13 September 2017|last1=Florance|first1=Loretta|last2=Younger|first2=Emma|work=[[ABC Online]]|access-date=13 September 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170913090952/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-09-13/rebel-wilson-defamation-damages/8936850|archive-date=13 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/sns-bc-as--australia-people-rebel-wilson-20170913-story.html|title=Rebel Wilson awarded millions in Australia defamation case|date=13 September 2017 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=13 September 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170913092858/http://www.latimes.com/sns-bc-as--australia-people-rebel-wilson-20170913-story.html|archive-date=13 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nBauer Media appealed the amount of the damages.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/bauer-media-to-appeal-rebel-wilsons-456-million-defamation-win-20171009-gyx148.html|title=Bauer Media to appeal against Rebel Wilson's $4.56 million defamation payout|first=Broede|last=Carmody|date=9 October 2017|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|accessdate=9 October 2017}}</ref> On 14 June 2018, Bauer Media won its appeal and the damages were reduced to $600,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/movies/court-slashes-rebel-wilson-payout-by-3-9-million-20180614-p4zld6.html|first=Broede|last=Carmody|title=Court slashes Rebel Wilson payout by $3.9 million|date=14 June 2018|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|accessdate=14 June 2018}}</ref> Wilson announced her intention to appeal the decision,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/celebrities/104741463/come-on-australia-rebel-wilson-slams-court-of-appeal-decision|title='Come on Australia': Rebel Wilson slams Court of Appeal decision|last=Moran|first=Robert|date=15 June 2018|publisher=[[Stuff.co.nz]]|accessdate=15 June 2018}}</ref> and lodged an appeal with the High Court on 11 July 2018.<ref>{{cite news|author=[[Australian Associated Press]]|title=Rebel Wilson to take defamation appeal to Australia's high court |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/jul/12/rebel-wilson-to-take-defamation-appeal-to-australias-high-court |work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=28 July 2018|language=en|date=12 July 2018}}</ref> The High Court refused the application on 16 November 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/celebrity/rebel-wilson-s-high-court-bid-rejected-20181116-p50gfr.html|title=Rebel Wilson's High Court bid rejected|first=Marnie|last=Banger|date=16 November 2018|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|accessdate=16 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nIn July 2011, Wilson became a spokesperson for weight loss and nutrition company [[Jenny Craig, Inc.|Jenny Craig]] in Australia.<ref name=\"JC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jennycraig.com.au/friendofjenny/rebelwilson/about|title=Rebel Wilson |publisher=Jenny Craig, Australia & New Zealand|accessdate=15 August 2011 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110720031826/http://www.jennycraig.com.au/friendofjenny/rebelwilson/about/ |archivedate = 20 July 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/confidential/rebel-wilson-seeks-to-slim-down-for-career/story-e6frf96x-1226097108580 |title = Rebel Wilson seeks to slim down for career |date = 19 July 2011 |work = [[Herald Sun]] |publisher = [[The Herald and Weekly Times]] |accessdate = 15 August 2011 }}</ref> In January 2012, Wilson told ''[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]]'' that she had lost {{convert|10|kg}} since signing up to the program.<ref name=\"StayingBig\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/why-rebel-wilson-will-be-staying-big-in-hollywood/story-e6frewyr-1226250311877|title=Why Rebel Wilson will be staying big in Hollywood| last1=Wigney|first1=James|last2=Halliwell|first2=Elle|date=22 January 2012|work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]]|publisher=[[News Limited]]|accessdate=21 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nWilson asserted that the producers of ''[[Pitch Perfect]]'' had refused to let her lose any more weight during filming, as her contract stated she must stay the same size. She said that once her film commitments were over, she would start her diet again to reach her target weight of {{convert|80|kg}}.<ref name=\"StayingBig\" /> In February 2013, she confirmed that she had ended her agreement with Jenny Craig the previous year.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/sydney-confidential/rebel-wilson-talks-on-split-with-jenny-craig/story-e6frewz0-1226580846065|title=Rebel Wilson talks about split with Jenny Craig|last=Christie|first=Joel|date=19 February 2013|work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]] |publisher=[[News Limited]]|accessdate=22 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nWilson and her ''Bridesmaids'' co-star [[Matt Lucas (comedian)|Matt Lucas]] lived together in [[West Hollywood, California|West Hollywood]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/showbiz/news/a403406/bridesmaids-rebel-wilson-matt-lucas-live-together-annoy-neighbours.html|title='Bridesmaids' Rebel Wilson, Matt Lucas live together, annoy neighbours |last=Wightman|first=Catriona|date=3 September 2012|work=[[Digital Spy]]|publisher=[[Hearst Magazines UK]]|accessdate=17 January 2013}}</ref> from September 2012 until 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/34384678/matt-lucas-on-rebel-wilson-moving-out-and-being-the-boss|title=Matt Lucas on Rebel Wilson moving out and being the boss|work=[[BBC News]]|date=29 September 2015|accessdate=13 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2015, Wilson stated her support for stricter American gun laws following the [[2015 Lafayette shooting]], stating, \"I don't like getting political but America you really have to follow Australia's example re gun laws. I don't remember a mass shooting in Australia since they [[Gun laws in Australia#Port Arthur massacre and its consequences|overhauled the gun laws]]. It seems like every week in America there's a shooting. I just want people to be safe, especially people that are doing one of my favorite things in the world\u2014going out to the movies to have fun.\"<ref name=gunlaws>{{cite news|last1=Derschowitz |first1=Jessica|title=Rebel Wilson says America needs new gun laws after Lafayette theater shooting|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2015/07/25/rebel-wilson-lafayette-theater-shooting|accessdate=27 July 2015|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date = 25 July 2015 }}</ref><ref name=gunlaws2>{{cite news |title = Rebel Wilson condemns US gun laws |url = http://www.skynews.com.au/culture/showbiz/celebrity/2015/07/26/rebel-wilson-condemns-us-gun-laws.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150816165154/http://www.skynews.com.au/culture/showbiz/celebrity/2015/07/26/rebel-wilson-condemns-us-gun-laws.html|archivedate=16 August 2015|url-status=dead |accessdate = 27 July 2015 |work = [[Sky News Australia]] |date = 26 July 2015 }}</ref><ref name=gunlaws3>{{cite news |last1 = Noyes |first1 = Jenny |title = Rebel Wilson speaks out about gun control after 'Trainwreck' shooting in Louisiana |url = http://www.dailylife.com.au/dl-people/celebrity-news/rebel-wilson-speaks-out-about-gun-control-after-trainwreck-shooting-in-louisiana-20150725-gikcs8.html?eid=socialn%3Afac-14omn0013-optim-nnn%3Anonpaid-25062014-social_traffic-all-organicpost-nnn-smh-o&campaign_code=nocode&promote_channel=social_facebook |accessdate = 27 July 2015 |publisher = Daily Life |date = 25 July 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Wilson paid $3.75 million for her Sydney harbourside home. The 1900s freestanding [[Victorian house]] underwent $900,000 of renovations. Wilson also settled on a Balmain investment apartment, a conversion of a historic mansion. The New York-inspired terrace home took three years to complete. Wilson paid $1.88 million off the plan in 2015 for the two-bedroom apartment.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.propertyobserver.com.au/forward-planning/advice-and-hot-topics/celebrity-property-news/95588-rebel-wilson-caught-in-landlord-trap-prevailing-in-the-sydney-property-front.html|title=Rebel Wilson caught in landlord trap prevailing in the Sydney property front|website=www.propertyobserver.com.au|access-date=3 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.realestate.com.au/news/inside-rebel-wilsons-global-property-portfolio/|title=Inside Rebel Wilson\u2019s global property portfolio - realestate.com.au|website=www.realestate.com.au|language=en-US|access-date=3 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Role\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2003\n| ''[[Fat Pizza]]''\n| Toula\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\